"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479555","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-22","<p>The full valuation of the public service pension schemes will commence in April this year. Following that full valuation process, which will take into account the new discount rate set in the Budget, the new employer contribution rates for the Armed Forces and Civil Service Pension Scheme will be set.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-03-22T16:37:18.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479555/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479555/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-17","Ministry of Defence: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, by how much he plans that his Department's contribution to public sector pensions will increase in 2019-20 and future years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","31664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479556","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) (through its Development, Concepts and Doctrine Centre) does not seek to define terms or elements of terms, particularly those applied in compound form, that are already in common use (i.e. &quot;warfare&quot;).</p><p>The MOD defines cyber activity as: &quot;To operate and project power in and from cyberspace to influence the behaviour of people&quot;. The OECD defines &quot;warfare&quot; as: &quot;engagement in or the activities involved in war or conflict&quot;.</p><p>The MOD describes the active engagement in the conduct of &quot;cyber operations&quot; within our lexicon as being: &quot;the planning and synchronisation of activities in and through cyberspace to enable freedom of manoeuvre and to achieve military objectives.&quot; This term applies to activities that include those conducted in war or conflict.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-03-22T16:34:21.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479556/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479556/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-17","Electronic Warfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what definition his Department uses for cyber warfare.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","31663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479557","Department for Education","false","2016-03-23","<p>The recommended national minimum allowance rates for fostering for 2016-17 will be published before the end of the financial year on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-23T18:09:25.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479557/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479557/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Foster Care: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to announce national minimum fostering allowances for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","31681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479558","Department for Education","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Department for Education has frequent contact with local authority officers and elected members on the subject of elective home education. Published guidance for local authorities is available on the GOV.UK website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/elective-home-education" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/elective-home-education</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-24T16:32:00.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479558/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479558/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Home Education: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to work with local authorities to ensure that the education provided to home educated children is effectively regulated and safeguarded.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","31680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479559","Department for Education","false","2016-03-23","<p>The Department for Education was not directly in receipt of programme funding from the European Social Fund. The European Social Fund programme for England that operated from 2007 to 2013 (extended to 2015) did, however, include monies for young people aged 14-19 who were not in education, employment or training or who were at risk of being so. This funding was administered initially by the Learning and Skills Council. From 2010 to July 2015, the funds have been administered by the Skills Funding Agency on behalf of the Young People’s Learning Agency and then on behalf of the Education Funding Agency. Given the nature of this European Social Fund programme operated by arm’s length bodies across a number of departments, without in depth analysis it is not possible to attribute funding for the period requested to particular departments. Such information will, however, be available in the Skills Funding Agency’s evaluation of the programme which will be published later this year.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-03-23T15:49:16.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479559/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479559/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Department for Education: European Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding her Department received from the European Social Fund (a) between 2007 and 2014 and (b) from 2014 to the last month for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","31638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479560","Department for Education","false","2016-03-24","<p>Career changers are an important source of new teachers and bring relevant knowledge and skills from their previous employment. The number of teachers returning to the profession has increased from 11,710 in 2011 to 14,100 in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015/16, 21% of new entrants to initial teacher training (ITT) courses were aged 30 and above. Our marketing campaign, Your Future Their Future, uses a range of advertising to promote teacher recruitment. As part of this we run a month-long ‘New Year New Career’ sub-campaign in January of each year which is dedicated to attracting more career changers to teaching.</p><p> </p><p>We provide specific support for career changers to make the transition to teaching and particularly for the subjects that are needed the most, which includes:</p><ul><li><p>The School Direct (salaried) route, which is specifically targeted at career changers with three years’ work experience and allows them to earn a salary whilst they train to teach.</p></li><li><p>Working with 18 School Direct lead schools to develop and recruit to flexible School Direct (salaried) courses in mathematics and physics, starting in September 2016.</p></li></ul><p> </p><p>Career changers can access support including bursaries or scholarships of up to £30,000 tax-free; advice and guidance from the expert advisers on the Get Into Teaching Line; help with arranging school experience to assist with their ITT application; and access to our free Train to Teach events.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-24T17:51:37.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479560/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479560/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479560/answer/previousversion/52943","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to encourage older professionals to enter the teaching profession for the first time.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","31711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479561","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>Figures from the initial teacher training data management system show the number of first year PGCE trainees from 2010:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Number of first year trainees on PGCE course</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p>19,931</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p>18,913</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p>20,195</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p>21,858</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>2014/15 performance profiles will be available from late July.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-22T17:30:11.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479561/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479561/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many people started studying for a PGCE in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","31712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479562","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>Regional Schools Commissioners (RSC) are supporting the development of high-performing multi-academy trusts (MATs). MATs will play a crucial role in the future school system, enabling academies to realise a wide range of benefits and providing the formal structure in which high-performing schools can support under-performing schools to improve.</p><p> </p><p>RSCs are responsible for approving new academies and intervening in underperforming academies and free schools in their area. In assessing schools proposals for becoming academies, RSCs will ensure schools joining existing trusts are matched to the right MATs, according to their need, the trust’s capacity and how together they will secure long term success. New academies will be matched with MATs who are able to evidence good or better performance and capacity for sustained improvement.</p><p> </p><p>With MATs taking on an increasingly important role, it is important that parents and the wider system can access information on how well they are leading their schools. Therefore, as we outlined in the recent White Paper, Education Excellence Everywhere, we will launch new accountability measures for MATs, publishing MAT performance tables in addition to the continued publication of, and focus on, inspection and performance data at individual school level.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-22T17:55:43.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479562/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479562/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Academies: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy that new academies should not join under-performing multi-academy trusts.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","31713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479564","Department for Education","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Department for Education has published guidance on ‘Listening to and involving children and young people’, which makes clear that in keeping with Article 12 of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child, local authorities (LAs) should take steps to ensure that the views of children are obtained and taken into account. This published guidance is available on GOV.UK at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/listening-to-and-involving-children-and-young-people" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/listening-to-and-involving-children-and-young-people</a></p><p> </p><p>The guidance is issued under s.176 of the Education Act 2002, which requires LAs to use guidance on consulting children when they exercise their functions in relation both to schools and to elective home education. It is for each local authority to decide how best to take account of the views of children who are being educated at home.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-24T16:56:19.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479564/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479564/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Home Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government has taken to assess whether the home education of children in consistent with Article 12 of the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","31691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479565","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>The expectation that all schools should become academies by 2020, set out in the 2016 Budget, did not include the early years. The government has already announced an ambitious plan to transform early years provision so that working families can receive 30 hours free childcare.</p><p> </p><p>The consultation on the National Funding Formula for schools sets out the government’s plans for replacing the arbitrary and unfair system for allocating primary and secondary school funding with a fairer system. Later this year, we will consult on proposals for a fairer funding system for all of the early years.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-03-22T17:52:43.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479565/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479565/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Pre-school Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to paragraph 1.89 of the Budget 2016, whether nursery schools are included in the plans to convert all schools to academies; how she expects the changes announced in the Budget 2016 to affect nursery schools; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","31594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479566","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>It is crucial that schools are effective in identifying their pupils with special educational needs and disabilities (SEND) and providing the right support to help these pupils fulfil their potential. We have recently made major reforms to the SEND system through the Children and Families Act 2014, so as to improve the support for children and young people with SEND. In the White Paper that we published on 17 March, <em>Educational Excellence Everywhere</em>, we have set out plans to embed those reforms and review our strategy to improve SEND provision. As part of this we will wish to look at options for how to identify and promote excellent SEND practice in schools. If My Honourable Friend has any specific proposals then I would be happy to receive them.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-22T17:59:06.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479566/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479566/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will establish an awards scheme for schools that have excelled in supporting children with special educational needs and disability similar to the scheme for pupil premium awards.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","31550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479567","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Department does not collect information on the nationality of looked after children. Information is available on their ethnic origin and this has been published in national table A1 of the statistical first release ‘Children looked after in England including adoption, 2014 to 2015’, which is attached and available on GOV.UK at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption-2014-to-2015</a>.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-22T17:24:23.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479567/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479567/answer","PQ31551_Children_Looked_After_2014_2015.xlsx","Children looked after - 2014 to 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479567/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Children in Care: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many non-UK children of each nationality are currently looked after in (a) foster care and (b) residential homes.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","31551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479568","Department for Education","false","2016-03-24","<p>Care leavers who are not British citizens usually receive the same range of support and services provided under the Children Act 1989 as British citizens. However, if they are aged over 18 and fall into one of the classes of ‘ineligible person’, under Schedule 3 to the Nationality, Immigration and Asylum Act 2002, they may only receive some of these. The most common class of care leavers who are ineligible persons are failed asylum seekers who have exhausted all appeals to remain in the UK.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-03-24T11:28:13.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479568/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479568/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Care Leavers: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what benefits and support services are not available to non-UK nationals leaving care that are available to UK citizens.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","31552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479569","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>Local authorities have a statutory duty under section 508B of the Education Act 1996 to make suitable travel arrangements for all eligible children attending their nearest suitable school. This includes children with special education needs (SEN) or a disability or mobility problem (including temporary conditions) if their SEN or disability or mobility problem means that they could not reasonably be expected to walk to the school. Being in receipt of the higher rate of the mobility component of Disability Living Allowance (a benefit with different eligibility criteria and assessment process administered by the Department for Work and Pensions) does not necessarily confer eligibility for free home to school transport but neither does it preclude it if the conditions above are met.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","31574","2016-03-22T17:32:30.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479569/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479569/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Disability Living Allowance: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether children who receive the higher rate of the mobility component of disability living allowance are considered to be eligible children for free school transport; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","31573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479570","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>Local authorities have a statutory duty under section 508B of the Education Act 1996 to make suitable travel arrangements for all eligible children attending their nearest suitable school. This includes children with special education needs (SEN) or a disability or mobility problem (including temporary conditions) if their SEN or disability or mobility problem means that they could not reasonably be expected to walk to the school. Being in receipt of the higher rate of the mobility component of Disability Living Allowance (a benefit with different eligibility criteria and assessment process administered by the Department for Work and Pensions) does not necessarily confer eligibility for free home to school transport but neither does it preclude it if the conditions above are met.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","31573","2016-03-22T17:32:30.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479570/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479570/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Disability Living Allowance: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether local authorities are obliged to provide free school transport to (a) all eligible children and (b) eligible children who receive the higher rate of the mobility component of disability living allowance.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","31574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479571","Department for Education","false","2016-03-22","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw. I have asked him to write to you and a copy of his reply will be placed in the House Library.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-03-22T17:33:05.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479571/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479571/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-17","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance and training Ofsted inspectors receive on applying the criteria for a good Ofsted grading in settings involving children with special education needs and disability.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","31549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479574","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Nuclear National Policy Statement, approved by Parliament in July 2011, identified eight potentially suitable sites for new nuclear power stations. The Government welcomes proposals for development at all eight sites. No proposals for development have so far been made for two of the sites – Heysham and Hartlepool.</p><p> </p><p>During the Budget, my rt. hon. Friend Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer announced the launch of phase one of a competitive process to identify which Small Modular Reactor designs could feasibly be delivered in the UK. Government also made a commitment to publish an SMR delivery roadmap to clarify the UK’s plan for addressing SMR related siting, regulatory approvals and skills issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will address the issue of site identification for SMRs, but no potential sites or siting criteria have been identified at present.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-22T15:28:27.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479574/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479574/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-17","Nuclear Power Stations:  Hartlepool and Heysham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether Heysham and Hartlepool are being considered as sites for large nuclear or small modular reactors.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","31538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479575","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-22","<p>The techno-economic assessment of small modular reactors does not conclude until the end of March at the earliest. We will then need to thoroughly review the reports. We will consider publishing at the appropriate point.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-22T15:29:08.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479575/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479575/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-17","Nuclear Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when the techno-economic assessment of small modular reactors is expected to be completed and published.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","31539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479576","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-22","<p>The techno-economic assessment of small modular reactors, which is due to conclude at the end of March at the earliest, will consider applications for SMRs in the UK context including how they could operate within the energy system.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-22T15:29:54.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479576/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479576/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-17","Nuclear Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department has made an assessment of the potential of small modular reactors as a heat source.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","31540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479577","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-11","<p>Under the Fourth Anti-Money Laundering Directive, which will be transposed into national law by June 2017, a politically exposed person is one who has been entrusted with a prominent public function domestically or by a foreign country. The Government's view is that the Directive permits a risk-based approach to the identification of whether an individual is a politically exposed person and, when identified, the Directive enables the application of different degrees of enhanced measures to reflect the risks posed. We will be setting out this view in our consultation which will be published shortly.</p><p> </p><p>This change should not prevent any individual in this category from gaining or maintaining access to financial services. We encourage financial institutions to take a proportionate risk-based approach when applying these measures.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-11T11:16:58.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479577/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479577/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479577/answer/previousversion/52832","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-17","Money Laundering: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate her Department has made of the number of its senior civil servants who will potentially fall under the provisions of the fourth EU Money Laundering Directive, 2015/849; and what assessment she has made of which of her Department's agencies or other public bodies will potentially be classed as holding a prominent public function for the purposes of that directive.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","31526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479578","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-11","<p>The Department for Energy and Climate Change received no funding from the European Social Fund between 2007 and 2014, nor subsequently.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-11T11:07:08.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479578/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479578/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-17","Department for Energy and Climate Change: European Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how much funding her Department received from the European Social Fund (a) between 2007 and 2014 and (b) from 2014 to the last month for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","31639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479579","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-21","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced in her speech that the Department will be launching a consultation in the spring, and that remains the intention.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-21T12:51:37.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479579/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479579/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-17","Coal fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, with reference to her speech of 18 November 2015, at the Institution of Civil Engineers, when her Department plans to publish the terms of reference and timescales for the consultation on closing all unabated coal-fired power stations.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","31604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479581","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-22","<p>The proposed public sector exit payment cap will apply to organisations classified as being within the public sector by the Office for National Statistics (ONS). This includes the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority’s sites, which are funded by the UK taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>It is envisaged that there will be discretion to relax conditions of the cap in exceptional circumstances, for example where there are genuine cases of hardship. This discretion, which would be considered on a case by case basis and which would be subject to Ministerial approval, will be provided for in the exit cap regulations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-22T15:30:24.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479581/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479581/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-17","Nuclear Decommissioning Authority: Redundancy Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 11 March 2016 to Question 30208, whether she plans to give Ministerial approval to relax the restrictions of the public sector exit cap on employees of the Nuclear Decommissioning Authority who leave work after 1 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","31669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479582","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs has not received any funding from the European Social Fund.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-24T15:54:14.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479582/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479582/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-17","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: European Social Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much funding her Department received from the European Social Fund (a) between 2007 and 2014 and (b) from 2014 to the last month for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","31640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479583","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Government submitted an initial EU Solidarity Fund application on Friday 26 February. We are in the process of refining our cost estimates and figures.</p><p>The United Kingdom’s Permanent Representation to the European Union submitted the initial application to the European Commission on the UK Government’s behalf and will continue to engage with them and the Department on the development of the application.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","31624 ; 31625","2016-04-26T14:58:38.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479583/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479583/answer","Stockton South","James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479583/answer/previousversion/52877","Biography information for James Wharton","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-17","Floods: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the total cost of damage caused by floods in winter 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","31626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479584","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Government's view is that the Directive permits a risk-based approach to the identification of whether an individual is a politically exposed person and, when identified, the Directive enables the application of different degrees of enhanced measures to reflect the risks posed. The Government will be setting out this view in a consultation which will be published shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The changes proposed under the Directive should not prevent any individual in this category from gaining or maintaining access to financial services. The Treasury regularly raises these issues with financial institutions and the regulator, and we encourage financial institutions to take a proportionate, risk-based approach when applying these measures.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-03-22T15:31:07.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479584/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479584/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-03-17","Money Laundering: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate her Department has made of the number of its senior civil servants who will potentially fall under the provisions of the fourth EU Money Laundering Directive, 2015/849; and what assessment she has made of which of her Department's agencies or other public bodies will potentially be classed as holding a prominent public function for the purposes of that directive.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","31525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479585","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>The National Food Crime Unit (NFCU) is initially focusing on establishing the scale and nature of food crime in the United Kingdom at a strategic level through developing intelligence sharing relationships across the law enforcement community and with the food industry. This will also enable the Unit to instigate investigative interventions by law enforcement partners and local authorities to identify and disrupt specific instances of food crime.</p><p> </p><p>At the end of this year, the Food Standards Agency (FSA) will review progress on food crime, in line with Professor Elliott’s recommendations following the horsemeat incident. This review will inform decision-making about the Unit’s future form and function including the need or otherwise for the unit to establish an in-house investigative capability.</p><p> </p><p>Intelligence analysts within the Unit have just completed the first ever Food Crime Annual Strategic Assessment (FCASA). The FCASA sets out the Unit’s developing understanding of food crime and will drive its work to ensure resources are focused where the threat to consumers and other interests is the greatest.</p><p> </p><p>The NFCU receives reports of suspicions of food fraud from a number of sources via many different routes. The FSA website directs users to a dedicated email address and telephone number for reporting these suspicions. Information is also received through local authority and law enforcement partners. Information received is analysed and, where appropriate, entered onto the Unit's intelligence database. Between 1 January 2015 and 18 March 2016, 793 such records were created.</p><p> </p><p>Establishment costs for the NFCU were minimal as the Unit initially evolved from a small but similar capability within the FSA. Total running costs to date are in the region of £579,000. Estimated costs for the forthcoming year are £1.2 million, subject to final allocations being agreed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","31534 ; 31535 ; 31536","2016-03-24T14:57:00.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479585/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479585/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","National Food Crime Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the (a) establishment and (b) running costs of the Food Crime Unit have been to date; and what resources have been allocated to that Unit in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","31533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479586","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>The National Food Crime Unit (NFCU) is initially focusing on establishing the scale and nature of food crime in the United Kingdom at a strategic level through developing intelligence sharing relationships across the law enforcement community and with the food industry. This will also enable the Unit to instigate investigative interventions by law enforcement partners and local authorities to identify and disrupt specific instances of food crime.</p><p> </p><p>At the end of this year, the Food Standards Agency (FSA) will review progress on food crime, in line with Professor Elliott’s recommendations following the horsemeat incident. This review will inform decision-making about the Unit’s future form and function including the need or otherwise for the unit to establish an in-house investigative capability.</p><p> </p><p>Intelligence analysts within the Unit have just completed the first ever Food Crime Annual Strategic Assessment (FCASA). The FCASA sets out the Unit’s developing understanding of food crime and will drive its work to ensure resources are focused where the threat to consumers and other interests is the greatest.</p><p> </p><p>The NFCU receives reports of suspicions of food fraud from a number of sources via many different routes. The FSA website directs users to a dedicated email address and telephone number for reporting these suspicions. Information is also received through local authority and law enforcement partners. Information received is analysed and, where appropriate, entered onto the Unit's intelligence database. Between 1 January 2015 and 18 March 2016, 793 such records were created.</p><p> </p><p>Establishment costs for the NFCU were minimal as the Unit initially evolved from a small but similar capability within the FSA. Total running costs to date are in the region of £579,000. Estimated costs for the forthcoming year are £1.2 million, subject to final allocations being agreed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","31533 ; 31535 ; 31536","2016-03-24T14:57:00.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479586/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479586/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","National Food Crime Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on establishing an investigative capability for the Food Crime Unit.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","31534"
