"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479616","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>NHS England and the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence are working together to develop future arrangements for the Cancer Drugs Fund, while the Accelerated Access Review (AAR) is being independently led by Sir Hugh Taylor with Office for Life Sciences’ support. The review’s final report is due to be published in the spring.</p><p> </p><p>Active steps are being taken to ensure that the future arrangements for the Fund and the final recommendations from the AAR are aligned.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-03-24T17:42:03.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479616/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479616/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what measures are being taken to ensure that (a) the outcomes of NHS England's proposals for a new Cancer Drugs Fund are aligned with the Accelerated Access Review (AAR), (b) the consultation outcomes are compatible with any forthcoming AAR recommendations relating to reform of NICE and (c) those programmes deliver consistent guidance on the medicines appraisal process; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","31678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479617","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>Following the March Budget 2015 announcement of £1.25 billion additional funding for children and young people's mental health services being available over the following five years, £143 million has been allocated for 2015-16. From this, £75 million has been allocated to clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to work intensively with key partner agencies to transform local services through delivery of their Local Transformation Plans (LTPs) to improve children and young people’s mental health and wellbeing, and £68 million is being spent centrally on workforce and system development to support local transformation. For 2016-17, £119 million has been included in CCG baseline allocations. The profile of spending for future years has not yet been fully determined.</p><p>The guidance for LTPs issued in August 2015, specified that plans had to be signed off by Health and Wellbeing Boards to ensure a shared ambition across all local partners, and included details of a robust bespoke assurance process for 2015-16, put in place by NHS England. This included the completion of detailed financial tracking templates, backed by a programme of regional and national support, to ensure that the additional money was spent for the purposes intended and that locally determined key performance indicators are being met. The intention from 2016-17 is to mainstream children and young people’s mental health as part of the normal NHS England planning cycle and to integrate LTPs into the new Sustainability and Transformation Plan.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","31688","2016-03-24T10:27:01.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479617/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479617/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how the Government is monitoring the effects of the £1.25 billion funding for child and adolescent mental health services.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","31689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479619","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>Following the March Budget 2015 announcement of £1.25 billion additional funding for children and young people's mental health services being available over the following five years, £143 million has been allocated for 2015-16. From this, £75 million has been allocated to clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to work intensively with key partner agencies to transform local services through delivery of their Local Transformation Plans (LTPs) to improve children and young people’s mental health and wellbeing, and £68 million is being spent centrally on workforce and system development to support local transformation. For 2016-17, £119 million has been included in CCG baseline allocations. The profile of spending for future years has not yet been fully determined.</p><p>The guidance for LTPs issued in August 2015, specified that plans had to be signed off by Health and Wellbeing Boards to ensure a shared ambition across all local partners, and included details of a robust bespoke assurance process for 2015-16, put in place by NHS England. This included the completion of detailed financial tracking templates, backed by a programme of regional and national support, to ensure that the additional money was spent for the purposes intended and that locally determined key performance indicators are being met. The intention from 2016-17 is to mainstream children and young people’s mental health as part of the normal NHS England planning cycle and to integrate LTPs into the new Sustainability and Transformation Plan.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","31689","2016-03-24T10:27:01.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479619/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479619/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to paragraph 1.233 of the March 2015 Budget, how much of the £1.25 billion funding for child and adolescent mental health services has been allocated.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","31688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479620","Department of Health","false","2016-03-22","<p>NHS England has operational responsibility for the Cancer Drugs Fund and has advised that it currently has no plans to publish all responses received on its consultation on the future of the Fund. An analysis of the consultation responses was published on 25 February 2016 and is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/cdf-consultation" target="_blank">www.engage.england.nhs.uk/consultation/cdf-consultation</a></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-03-22T16:46:16.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479620/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479620/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will place copies of all responses received to NHS England's consultation on the new Cancer Drugs Fund in the Library.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","31685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479621","Department of Health","false","2016-03-22","<p>We developed proposals in the consultation document based on a wide range of views we have heard over time including via numerous debates, representations from Members and several inquiries conducted by Parliamentarians.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, an independently facilitated meeting was held on 5 October 2015 with some members of three groups (Tainted Blood, the Contaminated Blood Campaign and the Haemophilia Society). The aim was to further inform the Department’s understanding of what matters most to members of these groups in terms of financial and non-financial support. A separate meeting was held in November with members of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Haemophilia and Contaminated Blood, where we sought views on proposals for reform ahead of consultation.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-22T11:08:55.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479621/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479621/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what consultation his Department conducted prior to the launch of its consultation on infected blood: reform of financial and other support.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","31701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479622","Department of Health","false","2016-03-22","<p>We have made no such assessment. Nabilone is not licensed for use in the treatment of multiple sclerosis.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-03-22T14:27:58.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479622/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479622/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Nabilone","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of making the drug nabilone available on the NHS for people with multiple sclerosis.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","31702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479623","Department of Health","false","2016-03-24","<p>This information is not collected. The organisation of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) services is a local matter.</p><p> </p><p>IBD is the collective name used to describe ulcerative colitis and Crohn’s disease. To support commissioners to deliver local services for people with Crohn’s disease and ulcerative colitis, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published the best practice guidance ‘<em>Crohn’s Disease Management in Adults, Children and Young People</em>’, in October 2012 and ‘<em>Ulcerative Colitis</em> <em>Management in Adults, Children and Young People</em>’ in June 2013.</p><p> </p><p>Both guidelines mention providing access to psychological support and the role it can play in patient care. In addition, patient education and patient information support are also highlighted as priorities for implementation. Commissioners should have regard to NICE guidance when delivering local services. The guidance can be found at the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/CG152/chapter/Key-priorities-for-implementation" target="_blank">https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/CG152/chapter/Key-priorities-for-implementation</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg166/chapter/Key-priorities-for-implementation" target="_blank">https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg166/chapter/Key-priorities-for-implementation</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","31694","2016-03-24T14:43:37.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479623/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479623/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many inflammatory bowel disease services have defined referral pathways in place to ensure that appropriate support is offered from a psychologist or counsellor with specialist knowledge of that condition.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","31695"
