"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480044","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-01","<p>The UK's representatives requested the International Court of Justice (ICJ) to declare the case inadmissible because that was our assessment following our analysis of the Marshall Islands’ claim. The detail of the UK’s legal arguments is contained in its written preliminary objections to jurisdiction and admissibility, as filed with the Court on 15 June 2015 and oral pleadings, as delivered at the public hearings held at the Court between 9 and 16 March 2016. The question of whether the ICJ has jurisdiction in a particular set of circumstances is a matter to be determined by the Court on a case-by-case basis in light of the relevant facts.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-04-01T11:38:04.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480044/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480044/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-17","Marshall Islands: Nuclear Disarmament","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why their representatives in the International Court of Justice on 14 March requested the Court to declare that it lacked jurisdiction over the claim brought against the UK by the Marshall Islands, or that the claim is inadmissible, and under what circumstances they believe the International Court of Justice has jurisdiction.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL7151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480045","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-01","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) prepares its forecasts on the basis of the current Government policy and does not look at alternative policy scenarios. Government policy is to remain within the EU. Therefore the OBR has not factored into its forecast the impact of a UK exit from the EU.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-04-01T12:30:13.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480045/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480045/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-17","UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Office for Budget Responsibility has produced its own forecast of the consequences of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL7152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480046","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-01","<p>European Regulation No 648/2012 (EMIR) establishes a strict supervisory framework for CCPs, which in the UK are regulated by the Bank of England.</p><p> </p><p>EMIR’s requirements – which continue to apply in the event of a merger or change of control of a CCP – include that a CCP must be sufficiently well-resourced to withstand extreme market events, including the simultaneous default of its two largest clearing members.</p><p> </p><p>In the event of a qualifying change of control the Bank of England must under EMIR also assess the suitability of the proposed acquirer and financial soundness of the proposed acquisition.</p><p> </p><p>Copies of the Bank of England’s 2016 report on supervision of financial market infrastructures were laid before Parliament on 4 March and are available in the House library.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL7342","2016-04-01T12:29:45.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480046/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480046/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-17","Financial Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will review the possible consequences for financial stability of the consolidation of central clearing houses.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL7153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480048","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-01","<p>The regulatory framework governing asset managers requires managers to take all reasonable steps to identify, prevent, manage and monitor conflicts of interest.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority are responsible for the supervision of firms to ensure consumers are protected and treated fairly.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-04-01T12:30:50.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480048/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480048/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-17","London Stock Exchange: Deutsche Borse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to monitor the role of institutional investors in voting their clients' shares regarding the potential takeover of the London Stock Exchange, in order to ensure that this reflects the best interests of the clients rather than the fund manager or related parties.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL7154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480049","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>There is a long established Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme that prospective parents can choose whether to participate in. The United Kingdom National Screening Committee recommendation on non-invasive prenatal testing does not change the choices available to prospective parents within the programme. We are satisfied that the UK is compliant with its obligations under the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities and that the Programme is compliant with all obligations under the Equality Act 2010. We would also note that English law does not recognise a foetus as a separate legal person.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL7092 ; HL7156","2016-03-23T15:04:04.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480049/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480049/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Pregnancy: Screening","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they are taking to ensure that the UK complies with its obligations under the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities if cell-free DNA, non-invasive prenatal testing techniques are made available to pregnant women on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL7155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480050","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>There is a long established Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme that prospective parents can choose whether to participate in. The United Kingdom National Screening Committee recommendation on non-invasive prenatal testing does not change the choices available to prospective parents within the programme. We are satisfied that the UK is compliant with its obligations under the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities and that the Programme is compliant with all obligations under the Equality Act 2010. We would also note that English law does not recognise a foetus as a separate legal person.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL7092 ; HL7155","2016-03-23T15:04:04.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480050/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480050/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to fulfil their obligations under the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities, and in particular Article 23, subsection 3.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL7156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480051","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>There is a long established Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme (NHS FASP) that prospective parents can choose whether to participate in. The UK National Screening Committee recommendation on non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) does not change the choices available to prospective parents within the NHS FASP. Guidance from the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists makes it clear that women and their partners should receive appropriate information and support from a properly trained multidisciplinary team, who must adopt a supportive and non-judgemental approach.</p><p> </p><p>NIPT testing as part of the NHS FASP will not be used to determine the sex of the foetus. Abortion on the grounds of gender alone is illegal.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL7160","2016-03-23T15:02:33.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480051/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480051/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Pregnancy: Screening","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the possible effects of normalising cell-free DNA, non-invasive prenatal testing techniques, in particular with regard to enabling sex-selective abortions.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL7157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480052","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>The information requested on total investment in Down’s syndrome research is not available. Spend on research funded directly by the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) is categorised by Health Research Classification System (HRCS) health categories including ‘congenital disorders’. There are no HRCS health sub-categories, such as for Down’s syndrome or other specific syndromes.</p><p> </p><p>To obtain how much the National Health Service invested in Down’s syndrome screening in the last year would incur a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Data on how much has been invested in the last year on support for people with Down’s syndrome is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-03-23T16:26:34.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480052/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480052/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Down's Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much has been invested in the last year in (1) Down’s Syndrome research, (2) Down’s Syndrome screening, and (3) support for people with Down’s Syndrome.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL7158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480054","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>There is support available for families with children born with Down’s syndrome. For many people this will involve an early intervention programme, to help support the child’s development and provide support to the family. This support will be delivered by health visitors and midwives.</p><p> </p><p>An early intervention programme can include speech and language therapy, physiotherapy to help with any muscle weakness, and individual home teaching programmes.</p><p> </p><p>Where a child has a special educational need, the local authority should also make support available to ensure the child has access to the same educational opportunities as a child without such a need. The Children and Families Act 2014 introduced a statutory framework for local authorities and clinical commissioning groups (CCGs), to work together to secure services for children and young people up to the age of 25 who have special educational needs or disability.</p><p> </p><p>General practitioners can provide an annual learning disability health check. Children and young people aged 14 and over who are on a general practice’s learning disability register are eligible to have a health check and a health action plan linked to this check. The health check and health action plan can inform a local authority’s annual review of young people with special educational needs from age 14 onwards to help them to prepare for adult life.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Act 2014 requires local authorities to undertake an assessment when an adult appears to have care and support needs. The assessment must involve the adult, their carer and anyone else they want to involve and consider the outcomes the person wants to achieve, their needs and how these impact on their wellbeing.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-03-23T16:26:13.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480054/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480054/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Down's Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to support individuals with Down’s Syndrome and their families.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL7159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480055","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>There is a long established Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme (NHS FASP) that prospective parents can choose whether to participate in. The UK National Screening Committee recommendation on non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) does not change the choices available to prospective parents within the NHS FASP. Guidance from the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists makes it clear that women and their partners should receive appropriate information and support from a properly trained multidisciplinary team, who must adopt a supportive and non-judgemental approach.</p><p> </p><p>NIPT testing as part of the NHS FASP will not be used to determine the sex of the foetus. Abortion on the grounds of gender alone is illegal.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL7157","2016-03-23T15:02:34.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480055/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480055/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Pregnancy: Screening","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will take steps to ensure that the issues highlighted in the Parliamentary Inquiry into Abortion on the Grounds of Disability of 2013, and in particular the finding that many parents are steered towards abortion and feel that they do not receive adequate information about other options, are not exacerbated by the introduction of cell-free DNA, non-invasive prenatal testing techniques.","false","Biography information for Lord Shinkwin",,"Lord Shinkwin","HL7160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480056","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-07","<p>These tax cuts provide significant support to local businesses. The Small Business Rate Relief measure announced at the Budget will mean 600,000 of the smallest businesses will not have to pay business rates.</p><p>Local authorities will be compensated in full for their loss of income as a result of these changes.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-04-07T15:38:45.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480056/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480056/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-17","Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to support local government in the light of their planned extension of business rate relief.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480057","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-12","<p>Government continues to work with partners to raise awareness and interest in STEM careers, including among females.</p><p>The Government launched the £30m Inspiring Science Capital Fund in January 2016, in partnership with the Wellcome Trust. The fund will help UK science centres invest in exhibitions and education spaces, and reach those who think science is not for them.</p><p>We also support STEM Ambassadors, a nationwide volunteer network of over 32,000 people from STEM companies or academia, who visit schools to encourage more young people into STEM.</p><p>In 2014 the Government helped to establish the industry-led Your Life campaign. Your Life has built a strong social media presence to inspire young people, particularly young girls, to study maths and physics as a gateway to exciting and wide-ranging careers.</p><p>DfE is funding programmes such as the Stimulating Physics Network (£2.15m in 2015-16) and the Further Maths Support Programme (£5m in 2015-16) to support schools and colleges to increase take up of maths and physics with a particular focus on engaging more girls.</p><p>109, 000 women were accepted onto STEM higher education courses in 2015. This represents an increase of 19.1% since 2010.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-12T11:07:45.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480057/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480057/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-17","STEM Subjects: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they plan to encourage more females into STEM professions.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480058","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-06","<p>The UK is a great place to start a business, with an increase of 760,000 businesses between 2010 and 2014. There are more women-led businesses in the UK than ever before - around 1 million (20%) of all Small and Medium sized Enterprises. But we know more needs to be done to ensure we create the right environment for women to start and grow their own businesses.</p><p>Women can benefit from the full range of wider business support available from government. This includes Start-Up Loans which provides funding and intensive support to new entrepreneurs (38% of Start-Up Loans have been awarded to women); and the New Enterprise Allowance which provides a business mentor and access to financial support for Jobseeker’s Allowance claimants who want to start their own business (37% of NEA loans have been awarded to women).</p><p>We have developed a specific web page on the Business is Great website for potential and existing female entrepreneurs to find out what help is available to them (<a href="http://www.greatbusiness.gov.uk/women-in-enterprise/" target="_blank">http://www.greatbusiness.gov.uk/women-in-enterprise/</a>). We are also currently undertaking research to increase our understanding of the best way to reach female entrepreneurs.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-04-06T14:07:43.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480058/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480058/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-17","New Businesses: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to support female start-up company founders in the light of the study by MIT, Harvard and Wharton Universities in 2014 showing that males are 60 per cent more likely to get funding.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480060","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-04","<p>We spend around £50bn every year on benefits alone to support people with disabilities or health conditions, with spending on Personal Independence Payment (PIP) and Disability Living Allowance (DLA) having increased by more than £3 billion since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The government has no further plans to make welfare savings, beyond those already announced. The government is committed to talking to disabled people, their representatives, healthcare professionals and employers to ensure the welfare system works better with the health and social care systems and provides help and support to those who need it most.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-04-04T13:31:36.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480060/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480060/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-17","Social Security Benefits: Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they propose to cut £4.4 billion from benefits for disabled people over the course of the Parliament.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480061","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-01","<p>The Government announced at Budget 2016 the biggest ever cut in business rates in England – worth £6.7 billion over the next five years. All ratepayers will benefit from the package and 600,000 of the smallest businesses, including many retailers, will not have to pay business rates again.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-04-01T12:28:14.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480061/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480061/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-17","Retail Trade: Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of criticism from the British Retail Consortium that proposed changes in business rates are inadequate.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480062","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>The respective Codes of Conduct for Ministers, officials and special advisers make clear the role of these individuals in developing and implementing Government policies.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-04-12T14:54:16.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480062/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480062/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-17","Government Departments: Newspaper Press","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bridges of Headley on 16 March (HL6672), whether the respective Codes of Conduct for (1) ministers, (2) officials, and (3) special advisers, allow them to draft letters to be signed by retired military officers or business people and then published in national newspapers.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL7166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480063","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-19","<p>Guidance on the nature and make up of extended ministerial offices (EMO) is set out in guidance published by the Government. The Guidance makes clear that EMOs are designed to support Secretaries of State and other Ministerial Heads of Departments. An EMO may include civil servants fulfilling the traditional private office role, special advisers and external appointees. The office may include support for policy formation, implementation, media, correspondence, relations with Parliament, as well as the traditional private office function.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-04-19T14:39:22.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480063/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480063/answer","HL7167 Attachment.pdf","Guidance Attachment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480063/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-17","Extended Ministerial Offices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bridges of Headley on 16 March (HL6552), how they define an "extended Ministerial Office", and for what purpose they are being established.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL7167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480064","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-23","<p>The 2015 Strategic and Defence Security Review announced that we will maintain our fleet of 19 frigates and destroyers whilst also conducting a concept phase assessment for the design and build of a new class of lighter, flexible general purpose frigate. This will mean that by the 2030s we can further increase the total number of frigates and destroyers. Joint Force 2025 will also include three replacement solid support ships, the two new Queen Elizabeth class aircraft carriers and at least two new offshore patrol vessels. Our national shipbuilding strategy, which we will publish later this year, will inform our plans.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-03-23T16:33:45.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480064/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480064/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-17","Warships","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, under the plans following the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, there will be more or fewer Royal Navy ships in commission by 2025 than the 57 currently.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL7168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480066","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-24","<p>Government commitments to maintain defence spending above the NATO target of 2 per cent of GDP, and to increase the defence budget by 0.5 per cent above inflation each year until 2020-21 were unchanged by the Budget.</p><p> </p><p>We will publish our national shipbuilding strategy later this year, which will lay the foundations for a modern and efficient sector capable of meeting the UK’s future defence and security needs. Furthermore, as announced in the Strategic Defence and Security Review, we intend to launch a concept study to design and build a new class of lighter, flexible, and exportable frigate so that by the 2030s we can further increase our total number of frigates and destroyers.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-03-24T15:25:26.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480066/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480066/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-17","Navy: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration was given in the Budget to the commitment made by the Prime Minister, when introducing the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, that there would be a bigger navy by 2030.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL7169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480067","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>The Department formally holds NHS England to account on its delivery against the research objective in the NHS Mandate, a process which will be rolled forward during 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>Progress has been made in the areas of participation of National Health Service organisations in research, with 98% of NHS trusts recruited into National Institute for Health Research Clinical Research Network Portfolio studies during the course of 2014/15, and 78% of NHS trusts recruiting to commercial contract studies in the same year. In addition, recruitment of participants into such studies increased in 2014/15 compared to the previous year to 618,453 participants. Recruitment into commercial contract studies is at an all-time high, with 34,885 participants in 2014/15; a 35% increase from 2013/14.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-03-23T15:08:11.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480067/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480067/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","NHS: Research","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Department of Health mandate to NHS England, which requires it to "ensure that the new commissioning system promotes and supports participation by NHS organisations and NHS patients in research funded by both commercial and non<b><i>-</i></b>commercial organisations", what progress has been made in achieving that objective, and how they record such progress.","false","Biography information for Lord Willis of Knaresborough",,"Lord Willis of Knaresborough","HL7170"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480068","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>Apprenticeship standards focus on the knowledge, skills and behaviours required to enable an apprentice to demonstrate mastery of an occupation and, as such, must meet professional registration requirements in sectors where these exist at the relevant level.</p><p> </p><p>The Nursing and Midwifery Council are involved in the development of the Degree Nurse Apprenticeship Standard and will formally be invited to become a member of the Nursing Trailblazer Group.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-03-23T15:08:28.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480068/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480068/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Health Professions: Apprentices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to involving appropriate regulators in the development of degree-level apprenticeships for nursing and other allied health professionals.","false","Biography information for Lord Willis of Knaresborough",,"Lord Willis of Knaresborough","HL7171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480069","Department of Health","false","2016-03-23","<p>No work has been undertaken to determine what impact the United Kingdom leaving the European Union would have on the education and training of registered nurses.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-03-23T16:26:46.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480069/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480069/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-17","Nurses: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the prospective impact on the education and training of Registered Nurses of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Willis of Knaresborough",,"Lord Willis of Knaresborough","HL7172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480070","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-24","<p>Local housing authorities do not receive subsidy from the Exchequer; the Localism Act 2011 abolished Housing Revenue Account Subsidy.</p><p>The Housing Revenue Account Self-Financing Determinations published in 2012 provided a once and for all settlement that allows local housing authorities in England to keep all their rental income in return for a rebalancing of housing debt.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-03-24T15:56:58.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480070/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480070/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-17","Council Housing: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the level of subsidy from the public purse provided for council housing.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480072","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-04","<p>Local housing authorities incur a range of costs when carrying out their statutory homelessness duties. They have powers to require households to pay reasonable costs towards both the accommodation that it secures for them and property storage costs, however they cannot require households to pay actual costs where these are more than those determined to be reasonable. Authorities determine what constitutes a reasonable cost by taking account of a household’s personal circumstances, its finances and the nature of the accommodation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-04-04T15:56:31.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480072/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480072/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-17","Council Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the difference between a local authority being able to recover (1) its expenses, and (2) its reasonable costs, in matters relating to its duties around housing legislation.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480073","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-04","<p>As at 1 March 2016, data provided to the department by Glenigan indicate that there were full planning permissions for 658,000 homes in England on sites on which work had either not yet started or completed. Of these around 55,000 (8 per cent) were on unstarted sites granted permission more than three years ago. Typically permissions for these homes will have expired.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-04-04T15:55:03.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480073/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480073/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-17","Housing: Planning Permission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the number of approved planning applications for housing that have yet to be built.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480074","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-07","<p>These tax cuts provide significant support to local businesses. The Small Business Rate Relief measure announced at the Budget will mean 600,000 of the smallest businesses will not have to pay business rates.</p><p>Local authorities will be compensated in full for their loss of income as a result of these changes.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-04-07T15:41:17.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480074/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480074/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-17","Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the additional expenditure reductions that will be required of local authorities following the announcement of the changes to business rates made in the Budget.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480075","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-04","<p><strong>The evidence behind the comments from Simon Stevens, Chief Executive NHS England, comes from the Public Health England report ‘Sugar reduction: the evidence for action’ published in October 2015. </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>The PHE report states that soft drinks are the largest single source of sugar for children and teenagers in England, and that consuming too much sugar can lead to weight gain, which in turn increases the risk of heart disease, type 2 diabetes, stroke and some cancers. It is also linked to tooth decay.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>This is why at Budget 2016, the Chancellor announced a new levy aimed at the producers and importers of added sugar soft drinks. The levy is designed to encourage companies to reduce the amount of added sugar in soft drinks and move consumers towards healthier choices. </strong><strong>The levy will from part of a wider comprehensive childhood obesity strategy which the government launch in the summer. </strong></p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-04-04T13:38:34.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480075/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480075/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-17","Sugar: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the comments of Chief Executive NHS England, in response to the sugar tax announcement in the budget, that "sadly soft drinks are now our children’s largest single source of diabetes-inducing teeth-rotting excess sugar."","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480076","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-01","<p>On 31 December 2014, the government published a response to the Call for Evidence on Credit Unions.</p><p> </p><p>In this response the government committed to considering the potential changes to credit union legislation highlighted by the Call for Evidence over the course of this parliament.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-04-01T12:37:33.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480076/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480076/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-17","Credit Unions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to review the legislation governing credit unions.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL7178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480078","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-04","<p>The Government is committed to creating a fair society in which all people, of whatever ethnic origin or background, are able to participate fully in society and realise their full potential. The Government deplores racism in all its forms and is determined to ensure everyone has the opportunity to get on in life, free from harassment and fear.</p><p>The UK has a strong and well-established legal framework to combat discrimination and hate crime, which protects all individuals, including Gypsies, Travellers and Roma, from racial and other forms of discrimination, and racially motivated crime.</p><p>The Government is taking action to improve the situation of disadvantaged people, including Gypsies, Travellers and Roma, in a number of the areas of concern identified in the Equality and Human Rights Commission report. These include improving educational attainment and attendance; tackling bullying; improving access to healthcare; supporting people into work and keeping them there; tackling hate crime; and addressing the over-representation of ethnic minorities in the criminal justice system.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-04-04T15:58:24.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480078/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480078/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-17","Travellers: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the account in the Equalities and Human Rights Commission's report <i>Is England Fairer?</i> of the discrimination faced by Gypsies, Travellers and Roma, and how they propose to address this.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL7179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480079","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The case for criminalisation is currently being reviewed by the department.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-03-24T10:36:02.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480079/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480079/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-17","Athletics: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, prior to hosting the World Athletics Championships in London 2017, they intend to introduce legislation to criminalise athletes who seek to enhance their performance in sport through banned doping programmes and gain selection over other athletes who do not.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480080","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The payments that UK Anti-Doping receives from third party countries ensures the UK's anti-doping programme is not compromised by its international work.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-03-24T10:34:56.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480080/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480080/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-17","UK Anti-doping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether UK Anti-Doping has adequate medical, administrative and financial resources to undertake international programmes for third-party countries, including a testing programme in Russia, whilst providing a comprehensive anti-doping programme in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7181"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480081","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","true","2016-03-24","<p>We want our sportsmen and women to win even more medals in Rio than they did in London 2012. That is why we continue to support elite sports funding, and why we secured an excellent settlement in the latest Autumn Statement - that will build on our Olympic and Paralympic success at the London Games 2012, and ensure we compete with the top nations in Tokyo 2020 and beyond.</p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">Whilst the ambition of winning more Olympic medals in Rio than London remains possible, the current evidence from UK Sport shows that it is highly probable Great Britain and Northern Ireland will have the best ever Olympic medal haul at an “away” Games.</del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">UK Sport analysis also indicates that despite an ever more competitive landscape the Paralympic team is set to win more medals than in 2012.</del></p><p> </p><p>UK Sport will publish agreed medal targets for Rio 2016 on a sport by sport basis in July.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-03-24T10:34:31.737Z","2016-03-24T12:33:54.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480081/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480081/answer",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480081/answer/previousversion/53288","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-17","Olympic Games: Brazil","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are on track to deliver their manifesto commitment to win more medals in Rio 2016 than in London 2012, and what progress is being made in preparations to deliver that commitment, broken down by sport.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480082","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Working Time Directive is a matter for employers. The UK Anti-Doping is not an employer of athletes.`</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-03-24T10:35:16.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480082/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480082/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-17","Sports: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have sought legal advice on whether the "Whereabouts" system operated by UK Anti-Doping during vacations taken by professional athletes meets the conditions of the EU Working Time Directive (2003/88/EC).","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480084","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The government’s recently published sport strategy ‘Sporting Future: A New Strategy for an Active Nation’ states that UK Sport and Sport England, along with the other Home Nations' Sports Councils, will agree a new UK Sports Governance Code by September 2016 to strengthen existing commitments, including the ambition for all sports’ boards to have at least 25% female representation by 2017.</p><p> </p><p>UK Sport and Sport England are already working with funded NGBs and partners to ensure best practice is adhered to when constructing job descriptions and writing adverts, and are working with expert organisations such as Sporting Equals and Women in Sport to ensure a more diverse range of people are aware of vacancies within the sector as they arise.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-03-24T10:35:46.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480084/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/480084/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-17","Sports: Governing Bodies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the current proportion of women on the Board of the British Olympic Association and on each winter and summer British governing body of sport represented in the Olympic and Paralympic movement, and how they intend to achieve their declared objective of requiring the proportion of women on each governing body to be at least 25 per cent by 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL7184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479031","Attorney General","false","2016-03-23","<p>The nationality of the offenders referred to the court is not collated centrally and could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-03-23T10:25:56.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479031/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479031/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479031/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-03-16","Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many unduly lenient sentences were given out to (a) British nationals, (b) non-British EU nationals and (c) nationals from outside the EU in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Tom Pursglove","Corby","Tom Pursglove","31332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479032","Attorney General","false","2016-03-23","<p>The available information is detailed in the following tables.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Law Officers’ </strong> <strong>Department</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contracted security providers </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Security Guards</strong> <strong>hourly pay rates</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Attorney General’s Office</p></td><td><p>Amey</p></td><td><p>Between £8.95 and £11.64 per hour</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Crown Prosecution Service</p></td><td><p>Bilfinger Europa Facility Management Limited</p></td><td><p>Between £8.09 and £10.31 per hour</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Law Officers’ </strong> <strong>Department</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contracted security providers </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Security Guards</strong> <strong>hourly pay rates</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p>Government Legal Department<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>MITIE (One Kemble Street office, London)</p></td><td><p>Between £12.51 and £15.57 per hour</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MITIE (Southern House office, Croydon)</p></td><td><p>Between £7.75 and £9.73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Walford Security (Riverside Chambers, Taunton)</p></td><td><p>£7.30 per hour</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><sup>1</sup>HM Crown Prosecution Service Inspectorate are tenants in the One Kemble Street building.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Serious Fraud Office is a tenant in a managed building where security guarding is outsourced by the landlord, the Canadian High Commission. The details of these arrangements are subject to the contract between the landlord, the Canadian High Commission, and the outsourced security provider. The decision about whether to publish details is a matter for the Canadian High Commission.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-03-23T10:34:11.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479032/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479032/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479032/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-03-16","Attorney General: Security Guards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 16 March 2016 to Question 30579, which outsourced providers the Law Offices use for security services; and if he will request information from those providers on the rate of pay for security guards providing services to his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","31326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479033","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-22","<p>Banks must make commercial decisions with regard to lending. The Government’s clear view is that the UK’s offshore oil and gas industry has a bright future and will remain a significant and important industry and energy supplier for the UK. The Government’s confidence in the sector was underlined in the tax reform package outlined by the Chancellor of the Exchequer in the Budget , worth £1 billion. In the Budget, the Chancellor also announced that the government is willing to consider proposals for using the UK Guarantees scheme for infrastructure where it could help secure new investment in assets of strategic importance to maximising economic recovery of oil and gas. Any proposals would also need to meet the existing criteria of the scheme, including in relation to commerciality and financial credibility</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-22T15:27:37.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479033/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479033/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479033/answer/previousversion/52536","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-16","North Sea Oil: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent assessment she has made of the availability of bank loans for oil exploration companies which operate in the North Sea.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479034","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-21","<p>The information requested is published annually and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website at the following location:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/governmentpublicsectorandtaxes/researchanddevelopmentexpenditure" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/governmentpublicsectorandtaxes/researchanddevelopmentexpenditure</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-21T15:19:31.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479034/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479034/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Research: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much public funding was spent on research and development in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479035","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-23","<p>As of 18 March 2016, my Department has received one piece of correspondence from an individual pub tenant and three pieces of correspondence from pub tenant groups on the appointment of the new Pubs Code Adjudicator, since the appointment was announced.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-23T16:35:09.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479035/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479035/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479035/answer/previousversion/52509","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Pubs Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what representations he has received from pub tenants and pub tenant groups on the appointment of the new Pubs Code Adjudicator.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","31376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479036","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-29","<p>It is the responsibility of local authorities to decide how to allocate funding for youth services according to local need, through the existing statutory duty (Education Act 2006, Section 507B). Government launched the Delivering Differently for Young People Programme to offer practical support to local authorities in exploring innovative and sustainable models for delivering youth services. Government continues to support the Centre for Youth Impact to work with youth organisations to undertake research to measure impact and demonstrate value to funders and commissioners. We are also committed to expanding National Citizen Service, which many youth sector organisations help to deliver. Government is taking new steps to encourage and enable social action. This includes a further £15m investment in the next phase of the Centre for Social Action. We want social action to become a lifelong habit.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-03-29T16:12:45.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479036/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479036/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-16","Youth Work: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps is he is taking to support the youth work sector; and if he will take steps to support that sector through sustainable funding, investment in research and incentives to encourage volunteering.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","31381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479037","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-01","<p>Details on 2015 calendar year Official Development Assistance (ODA) spend will be published in the National Statistics publication ‘Provisional UK ODA as a proportion of Gross National Income 2015’ on 1 April 2016, at department level. I am therefore providing values for the 6 year period 2009-2014.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) is building science and innovation partnerships between the UK and emerging economies through the Newton Fund, which began in 2014. The Newton Fund is subject to the International Development Act 2002, whilst all other BIS ODA spend is not. However, all of the Department’s ODA spending is in line with the aims of the International Development Act.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also introducing a new Global Challenges Research Fund of £1.5 billion over the next five years to ensure the UK’s world-leading research takes a leading role in addressing the problems faced by developing countries. This will mean that BIS’s ODA spend will increase over the current Spending Review period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="9"><p>Table 1. The value of Official Development Assistance (ODA) spent by the Department for Business, Innovation &amp; Skills, 2009-2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>£m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>total ODA</strong></p></td><td><p>37.3</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>47.9</p></td><td><p>40.0</p></td><td><p>48.0</p></td><td><p>48.5</p></td><td><p>79.0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>o/w ODA subject to IDA<sup>1</sup></strong></p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>4.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p><sup>1</sup> International Development Act 2002</p></td><td colspan="5"><p>source: DfID, Medical Research Council</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-01T12:28:14.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479037/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479037/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479037/answer/previousversion/52569","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the value was of Official Development Assistance spent by his Department in each of the last six years; and what proportion of that assistance was subject to the International Development Act 2002.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","31275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479038","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Department for Transport has held a number of recent meetings with the motor insurance industry, for example to discuss young driver safety and technology measures which impact on the cost of insurance.</p><p> </p><p>The Autumn Statement 2015 announced the Government will bring forward measures to reduce the excessive costs arising from unnecessary whiplash claims, and as the industry is competitive we expect average savings of £40 to £50 per motor insurance policy to be passed onto customers. Some insurers have already committed to pass on all savings to consumers as a result of the proposed changes.</p><p> </p><p>The pricing of insurance products is a commercial matter for individual insurers in which the Government does not seek to intervene.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-22T16:12:08.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479038/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479038/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-16","Motor Vehicles: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with motor vehicle insurance companies on reducing the level of insurance premiums.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","31297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479039","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>In CBI’s Best in Class report, the reference to the Swedish four box grid approach was part of a wider recommendation on allocating overseas resources for business support.</p><p>The UK Government recognises that it has a crucial role to play in supporting businesses that export and invest in international markets.</p><p>The Government is committed to focusing UK Trade and Investment (UKTI) overseas resources for business support in those markets that can deliver greatest benefit for the UK. UKTI uses similar publicly-available market data to Sweden (including GDP growth, political risk and the ease of doing business) in its assessment of export markets, but importantly this is just one input into the opportunity-focused, five-year rolling business planning process being developed to guide resource decisions.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-24T16:26:14.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479039/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479039/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Exports: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to Best in Class, published by the CBI in December 2015, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of Swedish four box grid approach to analysing the attractiveness of international markets.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479040","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-30","<p>The Department for Business Innovation and Skills supports British Sign Language (BSL), lip reading and managing hearing loss provision in England through the Adult Education Budget. Providers receive funding for this provision as they do for all other courses.</p><p><strong><em> </em></strong></p><p>In the academic year 2018/19, subject to readiness conditions being met, we intend to devolve the Adult Education Budget to certain Combined Authorities which have signed devolution deals[1]. In such areas, subject to necessary Orders being passed by Parliament, functions relating to the Adult Education Budget will transfer to the Combined Authority. The Combined Authority will assume responsibility for commissioning adult education provision, including in relation to BSL and sign language as it judges appropriate to meet local needs. Some providers, including Specialist Designated Institutions, are currently funded nationally. Their post-devolution funding arrangements will be confirmed in the coming months.</p><p> </p><p>Skills provision in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland is a devolved matter and the assessment and adequacy of BSL provision is the responsibility of the devolved administrations.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>[1] To date, deals have been agreed with: Sheffield City Region; Liverpool City Region; West Midlands; North East; Tees Valley; Greater Manchester; Greater Lincolnshire; East Anglia; West of England</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-30T13:00:19.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479040/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479040/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479040/answer/previousversion/52567","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Sign Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of the devolution of skills policy to local authorities on the development of British Sign Language and sign language interpreting skills.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","31401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479041","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not hold figures for UK footfall, however there are external sources that do collect these statistics.</p><p>The British Retail Consortium/Springboard Footfall and Vacancies Monitor publishes a monthly roundup of national changes in UK footfall.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-22T16:48:49.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479041/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479041/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-16","Retail Trade: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the percentage change in high street footfall figures was in each UK region in the last two years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479042","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-03-23","<p>According to figures taken from Oil and Gas UK’s latest Economic Report, it is estimated that over the course of 2015 there was a 15% reduction in jobs to 375,000 across the entire employment spectrum, including direct, indirect and induced jobs. For the previous year OGUK estimated that around 440,000 jobs were supported by the sector.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to supporting industry to avoid further redundancies and helping those who have unfortunately lost their jobs. We are working with the Scottish Energy Jobs Task Force to ensure that employers support those at risk of redundancy helping them to access future opportunities through training, education, and employment. In addition to this, my rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister announced in January a new Inter-Ministerial Group on oil and gas that will publish a UK Oil and Gas Workforce plan in the Spring.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-03-23T14:45:40.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479042/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479042/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-03-16","North Sea Oil: Termination of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many jobs were lost in the North Sea oil industry in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479043","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-07","<p>Information about the financial value of inward FDI stock by sector and source country is available from the ONS FDI Report (MA4, December 2015) and the value of direct investment from China by sector from 2011-2014 can be found in the attached table.</p><p>Please see tab 3.3 in the dataset: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/businessindustryandtrade/business/businessinnovation/datasets/foreigndirectinvestmentinvolvingukcompanies2013inwardtables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/businessindustryandtrade/business/businessinnovation/datasets/foreigndirectinvestmentinvolvingukcompanies2013inwardtables</a>.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-07T09:36:26.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479043/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479043/answer","PQ-31408-table.xls","Direct investment from China 2011 - 2014","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479043/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Foreign Investment in UK: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the value was of direct investment from China in each (a) sector and (b) industry sector in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479044","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The UK supports efforts to improve tax transparency. We initiated the international work on country-by-country (CbC) reporting to tax authorities during our G8 Presidency in 2013, calling on the OECD to develop a template for this as part of the BEPS project.</p><p> </p><p>The UK was the first to commit to implementing the OECD model with legislation in Finance Act 2015. We signed the OECD agreement to share the CbC reports with other tax authorities in January 2016 and issued our final CbC reporting regulations on 26 February 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that there is scope for greater transparency by pressing the case for public CbC reporting on a multilateral basis. As the Chancellor has said, this is something that the UK will seek to promote internationally.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:35:16.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479044/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479044/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Multinational Companies: Annual Reports","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to require large companies to publish a country-by-country report in their annual financial report.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479045","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>The new EU Audit Regulation (537/2014) prohibits the provision of tax services by audit firms to their audit clients. This includes services relating to tax avoidance. The prohibition will apply where those audit clients are banks, building societies, insurers and issuers of shares or debt securities on a regulated market in the EU (e.g. the main market of the London Stock Exchange). The Regulation was agreed by the European Parliament and the Council in 2014 and will apply from 17 June 2016.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-24T16:28:55.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479045/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479045/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Audit: Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to ban auditors from selling tax avoidance schemes to their audit clients.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479046","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-21","<p>I apologise to my hon Friend for the delay. I will reply shortly.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-21T16:29:46.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479046/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479046/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, when he plans to respond to Question 24897, tabled on 29 January 2016 by the hon. Member for East Worthing and Shoreham for Answer on 3 February 2016.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","31461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479047","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>The McKinsey team validated the early work undertaken by the BIS senior team, providing a perspective on the scale of the opportunity for operating cost savings and advising on deliverability, risks and any additional benefits.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-21T15:33:54.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479047/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479047/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the status is of the McKinsey report which informed the BIS 2020 departmental restructuring strategy.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","31484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479048","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>As set out in my answer of 4 February 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-01-27/24571/" target="_blank">24571</a>, this information can be found in paragraphs 31 – 36 of our November 2015 policy statement on the future of the UK Green Investment Bank (GIB) which can be found on the GIB pages of the GOV.UK website.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-24T16:27:01.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479048/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479048/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Environment Protection: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 4 February 2016 to Question 24571, what other government policy mechanisms are in place aimed at promoting high-risk green investment.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479049","Department for Education","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company (CEC) has made excellent progress in its work to transform the provision of careers, enterprise and employer engagement experiences for young people.</p><p> </p><p>The CEC is aiming for Local Enterprise Partnerships to recruit 50 Enterprise Co-ordinators and 300 volunteer Enterprise Advisers between September 2015 and March 2016. The Department for Education is in the process of agreeing the CEC’s funding and targets for the forthcoming financial year.</p><p>The number of full-time equivalent staff currently employed by the CEC is 18. Further recruitment will depend on the funding available to the company and its objectives for future years.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","31490 ; 31492","2016-03-21T14:33:47.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479049/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479049/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-16","Enterprise Advisers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2016 to Question 30445, what target she has set for the (a) number of enterprise coordinators to be appointed and (b) timeframe for those coordinators to be put in place.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","31491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479050","Department for Education","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company (CEC) has made excellent progress in its work to transform the provision of careers, enterprise and employer engagement experiences for young people.</p><p> </p><p>The CEC is aiming for Local Enterprise Partnerships to recruit 50 Enterprise Co-ordinators and 300 volunteer Enterprise Advisers between September 2015 and March 2016. The Department for Education is in the process of agreeing the CEC’s funding and targets for the forthcoming financial year.</p><p>The number of full-time equivalent staff currently employed by the CEC is 18. Further recruitment will depend on the funding available to the company and its objectives for future years.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","31490 ; 31491","2016-03-21T14:33:47.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479050/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479050/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-16","Careers and Enterprise Company: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2016 to Question 30445, how many full-time equivalent staff are working for the Careers and Enterprise Company; and what estimate she has made of what the final number of full-time equivalent staff at that body will be.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","31492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479051","Department for Education","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company (CEC) has made excellent progress in its work to transform the provision of careers, enterprise and employer engagement experiences for young people.</p><p> </p><p>The CEC is aiming for Local Enterprise Partnerships to recruit 50 Enterprise Co-ordinators and 300 volunteer Enterprise Advisers between September 2015 and March 2016. The Department for Education is in the process of agreeing the CEC’s funding and targets for the forthcoming financial year.</p><p>The number of full-time equivalent staff currently employed by the CEC is 18. Further recruitment will depend on the funding available to the company and its objectives for future years.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","31491 ; 31492","2016-03-21T14:33:47.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479051/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479051/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-16","Enterprise Advisers: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2016 to Question 30445, what target she has set for the (a) number of enterprise advisers to be appointed and (b) timeframe for those advisers to be put in place.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","31490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479052","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>Copies of the electoral register have been made available for sale in one form or another since at least 1832. Credit reference agencies purchase the electoral register because it provides proof to lenders that applicants for credit do in fact live at the address given and that they are not attempting to obtain credit fraudulently using a false name and address. Given the importance of credit in a modern economy, the then Government concluded in 2002 that this was in the public interest. The credit reference agencies are precluded by law from doing anything else with the electoral data, unless the data is also included in the edited register, from which individuals can opt out.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-03-24T10:21:12.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479052/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479052/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-16","Electoral Register: Credit Reference Agencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an assessment of the effect on electoral registration rates of introduction of a requirement to pass on electoral roll data to credit reference firms.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","31470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479053","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>Information requested is not held centrally. Pay below the Senior Civil Service is delegated to Departments and agencies.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-21T14:51:05.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479053/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479053/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-16","Civil Servants: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of civil service apprentices who have been appointed to date is (a) over the age of 25 and (b) paid at the rate of the national living wage.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","31485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479054","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-11","<p>All public appointments are made on merit following a fair and open competition in accordance with the Commissioner for Public Appointment’s Code of Practice. The Government is committed to increasing the diversity of public appointments. The Centre for Public Appointments in the Cabinet Office supports departments on all issues relating to the diversity of public appointments. Steps we are taking to increase diversity include streamlining the application process, placing an emphasis on ability over previous experience​ and increasing awareness of opportunities by using a central website, social media and engaging with a variety of diversity networks and groups.</p><p> </p><p>The Cabinet Office recruits staff in line with the Civil Service Commissioners Principles which ensures that candidates are selected based on fair and open competition and on merit. To reduce bias in selection, the Cabinet Office will be implementing name-blind recruitment methods from 1st April. In addition, recruitment and selection training, which has a core focus on raising awareness of unconscious bias, is also offered to all Chairs of recruitment panels.</p><p>On 24 March, we published our 2016 Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service. It provides a progress update on initiatives to increase diversity in the Civil Service, including cross-Government talent programmes aimed at under-represented groups. It also sets out how we will increase social mobility in the Civil Service. The 2016 Talent Action Plan is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/talent-action-plan-2016-removing-the-barriers-to-success" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/talent-action-plan-2016-removing-the-barriers-to-success</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-11T09:57:30.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479054/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479054/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-16","Cabinet Office: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to improve the diversity of (a) public appointments and (b) staffing in his Department.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","31422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479055","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-22","<p>A robust statutory framework exists for contingency arrangements in the event of a major industrial accident. This focuses on both accident prevention and multi-agency contingency planning delivered through the Civil Contingencies Act (CCA) 2004 and legislation addressing specific industrial hazards, including the Control of Major Accident Hazards (COMAH) Regulations 2015, the Pipeline Safety Regulations (PSR) 1996, and the Radiation (Emergency Preparedness and Public Information) Regulations (PEPPIR) 2001. The CCA requires multi-agency partnerships to assess the risks associated with industrial accidents and to undertake suitable specific or generic contingency planning. COMAH, PSR and REPPIR require site operators, local authorities and others to ensure effective arrangements are in place to respond to the onsite and offsite consequences of major accidents and provide for warning and informing those who might be affected.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-03-22T14:08:33.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479055/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479055/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-16","Emergencies: Industrial Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the Government's policy is on contingency planning for potential major industrial accidents.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","31279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479057","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p>All departments are now required to implement the new guidelines, published on 30 October last year, which set out how government buyers should source steel for major projects so that the true value of UK steel is taken into account in major procurement decisions.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-21T14:50:24.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479057/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479057/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-16","Government Departments: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the proportion of (a) domestically produced and (b) imported steel that was procured by each government department in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","31339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479058","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>Under the Fourth Anti-Money Laundering Directive, which will be transposed into national law by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/June_2017" target="_blank">June 2017</a>, a politically exposed person is one who has been entrusted with a prominent public function domestically or by a foreign country. This would include some senior civil servants, such as ambassadors and chargés d'affaires. The Government's view is that the Directive permits a risk-based approach to the identification of whether an individual is a politically exposed person and, when identified, the Directive enables the application of different degrees of enhanced measures to reflect the risks posed. The Government will be setting out this view in a consultation which will be published shortly.</p><p> </p><p>The changes proposed under the Directive should not prevent any individual in this category from gaining or maintaining access to financial services. The Treasury regularly raises these issues with financial institutions and the regulator, and we encourage financial institutions to take a proportionate, risk-based approach when applying these measures.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-21T15:28:24.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479058/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479058/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Money Laundering: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the number of its senior civil servants who will potentially fall under the provisions of the 4th EU Money Laundering Directive, 2015/849; and what assessment he has made of (a) whether the Financial Conduct Authority and (b) which of his Department's other agencies and public bodies will potentially be classed as holding a prominent public function for the purposes of that directive.","false","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker","31345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479059","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-29","<p>From the total funding of £180 million the Department for Transport has made available to assist local highway authorities affected by this winter storms, including £130 million as announced in the Budget 2016, we have agreed to allocate a total of £25 million to Calderdale Council to help repair damage to the local highway infrastructure for which they are responsible. This includes the £5.5 million announced in January 2016 to help replace Elland Bridge.</p><p><br>This funding is in addition to the funding of £‎20.5 million we are providing to the council for local highways maintenance funding to 2020/21.</p><p><br></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-29T11:17:01.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479059/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479059/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-16","Roads: Calderdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to page 75 of the Budget, how much of the £130 million announced for repairs of roads and bridges he plans will be spent in Calderdale; and when he expects Calderdale council to be in receipt of such funds.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","31355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479060","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The Government is committed to supporting pubs and other licensed hospitality firms. The sector will benefit from the changes announced at Budget 2016. These include cutting business rates for all properties in England with Barnett consequentials for Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland to introduce equivalent measures if they so wish.</p><p> </p><p>Reforms to stamp duty land tax on non-residential property transactions will cut the tax for many small businesses purchasing property. Budget 2016 also announced the corporation tax rate will be cut to 17% in 2020 and that the duty rates on beer, spirits and most ciders will be frozen this year.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:32:35.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479060/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479060/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Licensed Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to support the licensed hospitality sector to mitigate the effects of (a) wage rate inflation and (b) reduced demand for drink and food-led outlets.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","31361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479061","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Government agrees that the maintenance of sustainable debt levels is a critical factor for achieving poverty reduction. The UK has provided more than £5 billion in debt relief since 1996 under the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries and Multilateral Debt Relief Initiatives, and will continue to promote debt sustainability internationally.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also committed to supporting developing countries to access their domestic tax revenues through our efforts in driving the G20-OECD Base Erosion and Profit Shifting project and our commitment to funding tax capacity building in developing countries bilaterally and multilaterally - including through the direct provision of technical assistance by the UK to tackle tax avoidance.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-22T14:10:44.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479061/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479061/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Debts: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will issue a response to Early Day Motion 68, Prevention of debt crisis in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","31311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479062","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The latest available data for the numbers of individual taxpayers with self-employment income, by constituency level, is for 2012-13. There were estimated to be 4,000 individuals with self-employment income in Cardiff South and Penarth out of 48,000 with income from any source.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates are based on the Survey of Personal Incomes and are taken from table 3.15 of the HM Revenue and Customs Personal Income statistics publication. The estimate for 2013-14 is due to be published on the 31st March 2016.</p><p> </p><p>No information on the purpose for individuals registering for Self Assessment is collected.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-21T17:08:58.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479062/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479062/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Self-employed: Cardiff South and Penarth","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people were registered with HM Revenue and Customs as self-employed (a) wholly and (b) partly for the purposes of tax and national insurance in Cardiff South and Penarth constituency in each of the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","31274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479063","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has not undertaken a separate value for money review on the decision to relocate staff from Phoenix House, Oldham to Manchester. I refer you to my <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-02-29/28866/" target="_blank">answer</a> of 8 March.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:44:35.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479063/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479063/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Revenue and Customs: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answers of 3 February 2016 to Question 24298 and 8 March 2016 to Question 28866, on Revenue and Customs: Greater Manchester, whether any value for money review was undertaken on the decision to relocate staff from Phoenix House, Oldham to Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","31281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479064","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>It is not possible for HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to provide details of any action taken in connection with these organisations.</p><p> </p><p>In the March 2015 Budget, the Government challenged the accountancy and tax professional bodies to improve how they deal with their members who promote tax avoidance schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The professional bodies have responded positively to this challenge and are working with HMRC to agree a new standard to which their members will need to adhere.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","31417 ; 31418 ; 31419","2016-03-29T10:43:14.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479064/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the judgment in Schofield v HM Revenue and Customs [2012] EWCA Civ 927 (11 July 2012), what steps his Department has taken against PricewaterhouseCoopers for designing and marketing the tax avoidance scheme rejected by the court.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479065","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>Tax policy is a matter for national governments and direct tax files are subject to a unanimous vote in the Council. The Government has made it very clear to the European Commission that the UK will not sign up to the CCCTB, or any other measure that would undermine our tax sovereignty or risk harming the competitiveness and growth prospects of the Single Market.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:42:00.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479065/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479065/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Business: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the European Commission about introduction of the Common Consolidated Corporate Tax Base.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479066","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>Housing and planning in Wales are the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-21T15:39:59.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479066/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479066/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Garden Communities: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.123 of the Budget 2016, whether the (a) proposed legislation to make it easier for local authorities to work together to create new garden towns and (b) consultation on a second wave of Compulsory Purchase Order reforms will apply to Wales.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","31428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479067","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Financial Policy Committee of the Bank of England publishes the growth in the notional value of derivatives (see link below).</p><p><a href="http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/fsr/2015/scrdec15.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/fsr/2015/scrdec15.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>This indicates that notional derivatives growth was -25.9% as of 20 November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Policy’s Committee’s indicator includes all major UK banks.</p><p> </p><p>Individual bank derivatives exposures may also be found in their published annual reports.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","31436","2016-03-21T15:51:52.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479067/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479067/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the notional value is of derivatives held by banks regulated by the UK authorities.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479068","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Financial Policy Committee of the Bank of England publishes the growth in the notional value of derivatives (see link below).</p><p><a href="http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/fsr/2015/scrdec15.xlsx" target="_blank">http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Documents/fsr/2015/scrdec15.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>This indicates that notional derivatives growth was -25.9% as of 20 November 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The Financial Policy’s Committee’s indicator includes all major UK banks.</p><p> </p><p>Individual bank derivatives exposures may also be found in their published annual reports.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","31435","2016-03-21T15:51:52.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479068/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479068/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the exposure to derivatives is of each bank holding a deposit-taking licence.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479069","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Sheffield Heeley on 22 February to UIN: 26788.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-21T14:51:18.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479069/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479069/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-03-16","Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many bidders for central government contracts have been debarred in accordance with the promoting tax compliance and procurement rules introduced in 2013.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479070","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>HM Treasury have the following secondments in as at 29<sup>th</sup> February 2016:-</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Deloitte Touche</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ernst and Young</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>KPMG</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PriceWaterhouseCoopers</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-23T13:56:11.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479070/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479070/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Treasury: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff are seconded to his Department by (a) KPMG, (b) PricewaterhouseCoopers, (c) Deloitte and (d) Ernst & Young.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479071","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-22","<p>Milk-based drinks, including flavoured milks, are not in scope of the levy. Milk contains calcium and other nutrients which are vital to children’s health.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-22T14:08:16.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479071/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479071/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Sugar: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 33 of the Budget 2016, whether flavoured milks will be exempt from the sugar levy.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","31452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479072","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The Government is committed to countering tax avoidance to ensure all taxpayers pay their fair share. At Budget 2016, the Chancellor announced a comprehensive package of measures to tackle tax avoidance and aggressive tax planning, and tax evasion by individuals and businesses. Overall, this will raise £12 billion by 2020-21.</p><p> </p><p>We keep our policy on countering tax avoidance under continuous review to respond to emerging risks.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:40:54.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479072/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479072/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will appoint an independent commission to investigate the role of PricewaterhouseCoopers, KPMG, Ernst & Young and Deloitte in designing, selling and implementing tax avoidance schemes.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479073","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>At Budget 2016 the Government announced an intention to establish a Broadband Investment Fund. No decision has yet been made on the amount that will be invested. The next stage of the process will see the Government procure a fund manager to raise and manage the fund.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-21T15:31:03.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479073/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Broadband: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 65 of the Budget 2016, how much he has allocated to establish the new Broadband Investment Fund in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479074","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>Budget 2016 announced that the government will provide £20 million across 2016-17 and 2017-18 to extend the First World War Centenary cathedral repairs fund. £10 million of this is financed through new exchequer funding and listed in Table 2.1 on page 86 of the Budget. The remaining £10 million is financed from within the existing DCMS resource budget.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-23T14:32:17.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479074/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479074/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Cathedrals: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to pages 86 and 122 of the Budget 2016, why the fiscal impact of establishing the £20 million Cathedrals Repairs Fund is £10 million.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479075","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>HM Revenue and Customs encourages people to come forward with information in a number of ways, and is already able to offer financial rewards to those who provide us with significant information relating to tax evasion or avoidance. The best way to do so is kept under review.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:36:20.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479075/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479075/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to provide that whistleblowers whose evidence leads to a successful prosecution of tax evasion or avoidance receive a portion of the tax penalties levied on the guilty party.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479076","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>Following the announcement made at the Budget, the Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) launched the first phase of a competition to identify the best value small modular reactor for the UK on the 17<sup>th</sup> March. This development builds on a previous announcement, made at Autumn Statement 2015, that DECC would conduct this competition to help pave the way towards building one of the world’s first small modular reactors in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The relevant documentation for the competition is available at:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/small-modular-reactors</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-21T17:24:25.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479076/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479076/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Nuclear Reactors","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.248 of the Budget 2016, to which Department bids to help develop the next generation of small modular reactors will be submitted.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","31398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479077","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Government will ensure that HM Revenue and Customs has the resources it requires to implement the package of measures announced at Budget 2016 to tackle avoidance and evasion.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-21T17:12:43.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479077/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479077/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.215 of the Budget 2016, whether he plans to make additional resources available to HM Revenue and Customs to implement the comprehensive package of measures to tackle tax avoidance and evasion.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","31399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479078","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The Budget announced that over £150m will be invested in flood defence schemes in Leeds, York, Calder Valley, Carlisle and wider Cumbria. Funding will be allocated accordingly: Leeds (£35m), Cumbria (excluding Carlisle) (£33m), Carlisle (up to £25m), Calder Valley (£35m), and York (£45m). This funding will be delivered over the period 2016-17 to 2020-21.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-29T10:38:45.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479078/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479078/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Flood Control: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 64 of the Budget 2016, how much of the £150 million announced for flood defence schemes he plans will be spent in (a) Leeds, (b) Cumbria, (c) Calderdale and (d) York; and when he expects that funding to be delivered.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","31354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479079","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Budget formally announced the opening of discussions with local partners and the Scottish Government towards a City Deal for Edinburgh and South East Scotland. No deadline has been set for their conclusion or for implementation of a Deal, but we will work with all parties to ensure that discussions proceed at an appropriate pace for delivering the best Deal to drive economic growth in Edinburgh and South East Scotland.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","31388","2016-03-21T17:22:20.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479079/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479079/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Local Government: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department has set a deadline for implementation of a city deal for Edinburgh and South East Scotland.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","31386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479080","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-01","<p>The first wave of Science and Innovation Audits, including the Edinburgh and the Lothians audit, were announced at Budget on 16<sup>th</sup> March. Consortia going through Wave 1 have been selected to represent a cross section of approaches, geographical areas, and capacity to engage actively in developing the methodology. Initial planning meetings will commence shortly and we expect the project to be delivered by the Autumn.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-01T12:30:36.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479080/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479080/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479080/answer/previousversion/52570","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Science: Lothian","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to page 69 of the Budget 2016, when his Department plans to start the science and innovation audit in Edinburgh and the Lothians.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","31387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479081","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Budget formally announced the opening of discussions with local partners and the Scottish Government towards a City Deal for Edinburgh and South East Scotland. No deadline has been set for their conclusion or for implementation of a Deal, but we will work with all parties to ensure that discussions proceed at an appropriate pace for delivering the best Deal to drive economic growth in Edinburgh and South East Scotland.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","31386","2016-03-21T17:22:20.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479081/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479081/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Local Government: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he expects discussions to begin with partners in the Edinburgh and South East Scotland City Deal.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","31388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479082","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>ISA statistics for the latest available tax year (2012-13) are published on the GOV.UK website.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-21T15:48:42.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479082/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Individual Savings Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the annual amount saved in ISA accounts in each income group; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","31390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479083","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>Public sector net debt is forecast to fall from 2016-17 to the end of the Parliament, reaching 77.2% of GDP by the end of 2019-20. The OBR’s latest forecast is that the level of cash debt at the end of 2015-16 will be £1591 billion, down from £1599 billion in its November forecast. Debt as a share of GDP is forecast to rise from 83.3% in 2014-15 to 83.7% of GDP at the end of 2015-16 because the economy is smaller in nominal terms in 2015-16 than forecast in November, largely due to lower inflation. The government has also delayed the sale of the remaining shares in Lloyds Banking Group as a result of market conditions.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-23T14:34:36.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479083/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479083/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the change in the debt to gross domestic product ratio in 2014-15 and 2015-16; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","31391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479084","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>Government action to reward work and reform benefits has delivered a strong labour market which has seen the employment rate grow more than any other G7 country since early 2010 (Q1), and in the three months to January it stood at 74.1 per cent – the highest since records began.</p><p> </p><p>The government believes it is possible to maintain a strong labour market and improve productivity performance, and this why it has set out a comprehensive programme of structural reform in the productivity plan – “Fixing the Foundations” – with further measures included in Budget 2016.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-23T14:41:49.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479084/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479084/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the effect of changes in the participation rate on economic productivity; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","31392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479085","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The European Commission’s annual Financial Report provides calendar year historical contributions figures.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:30:47.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479085/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479085/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much in VAT-based contributions the UK paid to the EU in each of the last 10 years; and if he will estimate the amount of such contributions in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","31474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479086","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>Analysis undertaken by the independent Migration Advisory Committee in 2012 shows that higher levels of net migration will, all else equal, increase the growth rate of the potential labour supply and therefore the rate of growth of overall GDP.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-23T14:33:23.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479086/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479086/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the effect of immigration on the UK's GDP in the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","31494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479087","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>It is not possible for HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to provide details of any action taken in connection with these organisations.</p><p> </p><p>In the March 2015 Budget, the Government challenged the accountancy and tax professional bodies to improve how they deal with their members who promote tax avoidance schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The professional bodies have responded positively to this challenge and are working with HMRC to agree a new standard to which their members will need to adhere.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","31410 ; 31417 ; 31418","2016-03-29T10:43:14.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479087/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479087/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the judgment in Iliffe News and Media Ltd & Ors v Revenue and Customs [2012] UKFTT 696 (TC) (1 November 2012), what steps his Department has taken against Ernst & Young for designing and marketing the tax avoidance scheme rejected by the court.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479088","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>Due to companies being able to make a Patent Box election up to two years after the relevant accounting period, we will not be able to get full figures for the first year of the Patent Box until April 2016. The following figures are therefore projections.</p><p> </p><p>The estimated amounts of Patent Box relief can be found at the link below;</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/487119/Dec15_expenditure_reliefs_Final.xlsx.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/487119/Dec15_expenditure_reliefs_Final.xlsx.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>About 480 companies made Patent Box relief elections for the first year 2013-14 alone.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:37:40.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479088/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479088/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Patents: Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many companies have applied for the lower rate of corporation tax under Patent Box.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479089","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>It is not possible for HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to provide details of any action taken in connection with these organisations.</p><p> </p><p>In the March 2015 Budget, the Government challenged the accountancy and tax professional bodies to improve how they deal with their members who promote tax avoidance schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The professional bodies have responded positively to this challenge and are working with HMRC to agree a new standard to which their members will need to adhere.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","31410 ; 31417 ; 31419","2016-03-29T10:43:14.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479089/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479089/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Supreme Court's judgment in UBS AG & Anor v Revenue and Customs [2016] UKSC 13 (9 March 2016), what steps his Department has taken against Deloitte for designing and marketing the tax avoidance scheme rejected by the court.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479090","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>It is not possible for HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) to provide details of any action taken in connection with these organisations.</p><p> </p><p>In the March 2015 Budget, the Government challenged the accountancy and tax professional bodies to improve how they deal with their members who promote tax avoidance schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The professional bodies have responded positively to this challenge and are working with HMRC to agree a new standard to which their members will need to adhere.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","31410 ; 31418 ; 31419","2016-03-29T10:43:14.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479090/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479090/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the judgment in Stagecoach Group PLC & Anor v Revenue and Customs [2016] UKFTT 120 (tc) (10 February 2016), what steps his Department has taken against KPMG for designing and marketing the tax avoidance scheme rejected by the court.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","31417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479091","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>‘Showcase’ bids were identified, with the help of departmental expertise, that were innovative, in line with the aims of government policy, and likely to provide strong value for money. The bids selected represent a range of different initiatives to benefit women across the whole of the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, in recognition of the very high level of interest received, the government has also allocated funding to the Women’s Fund for Scotland, Comic Relief and Rosa who have specialist experience in this area, to disburse funding to a range of grassroots women’s organisations. These funds mean further awards will be made to a high number of charities in this sector.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-23T13:44:13.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479091/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479091/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, who was involved in the process to select which charities would receive funding from the Tampon Tax Fund.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","31498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479092","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>As announced at Autumn Statement 2015, the Tampon Tax Fund is a £15 million annual fund to support women’s charities, equivalent to the amount of VAT raised on sanitary products. The Chancellor announced initial donations at Autumn Statement totalling £5m. Further grants totalling £12 million have been announced at this Budget.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has introduced legislation in the Finance Bill to enable the zero rate of VAT for women’s sanitary products.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-23T16:58:49.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479092/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479092/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 1.144 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 and to paragraph 2.16 of the Budget 2016, for what reason only £12 million of the £15 million annual fund has been committed.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","31499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479093","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>‘Showcase’ bids were identified, with the help of departmental expertise, that were innovative, in line with the aims of government policy, and likely to provide strong value for money.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, in recognition of the very high level of interest received, the government has also allocated funding to the Women’s Fund for Scotland, Comic Relief and Rosa who have specialist experience in this area, to disburse funding to a range of grassroots women’s organisations. These funds mean further awards will be made to a high number of charities in this sector.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-23T13:42:47.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479093/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479093/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Sanitary Protection: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what criteria is applied when determining which charities should receive funding from the Tampon Tax Fund.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","31497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479094","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-29","<p>The UK’s net contribution to the EU in 2006, including rebate and total receipts from the EU, can be found in the tables appended in the EU’s Financial Report 2014:</p><p> </p><p>ec.europa.eu/budget/library/biblio/documents/2014/Internet%20tables%202000-2014.xls</p><p> </p><p>No comparable figure can be provided for 2015-16 as outturn data will only become available later in the year.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-03-29T10:40:00.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479094/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479094/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","EU Budget: Contributions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the UK's net financial contribution to the EU budget (a) was in 2006 and (b) is in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","31516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479095","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The government is aware of the announcement by the London Stock Exchange Group and Deutsche Boerse that they have reached agreement on a merger of equals. This is a commercial transaction and subject to regulatory and other relevant approvals. The Government will not be commenting at this stage.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-03-21T15:49:57.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479095/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479095/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","London Stock Exchange: Deutsche Borse","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the proposed merger between the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse on London's role as a global financial centre.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","31518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479096","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-23","<p>As noted in the 2012 report by the Migration Advisory Committee the empirical literature suggests that the impact of migration on productivity may be mixed and heavily dependent on the type of migrant coming to the UK. Migrants may increase productivity either through a simple ‘batting average’ effect if they work in higher productivity roles relative to the average for non-migrants, or through increasing the productivity of UK workers through greater specialisation and knowledge transfer.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-23T14:36:14.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479096/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479096/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-16","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of immigration on the level of economic productivity over the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","31493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479097","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-29","<p>No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why we have increased our central investment for homelessness to £139 million over the next four years, and protected homelessness prevention funding to local authorities, totalling £315 million.</p><p>We know sleeping rough is rarely the result of a personal housing crisis alone and that the most entrenched rough sleepers often have complex needs, including mental health difficulties or addiction. That is why we are investing £10 million in an innovative new national Social impact Bonds Fund to help address these complex needs in order to help entrenched rough sleepers move off the streets. Through my Ministerial Working Group on Homelessness, I am working with ministerial colleagues across government including the Department of Health, to develop actions to address these underlying causes of homelessness.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-03-29T11:58:45.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479097/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479097/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-16","Sleeping Rough: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of rough sleepers has mental health issues; and what plans he has to address that issue.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","31421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479098","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-05-04","<p>The attached table below shows the number of called-in planning decisions issued by the Secretary of State during each of the last 10 years issued more than three months after the report was received.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year decision was issued</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Decisions issued more than 3 months after Inspector’s report was received</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2006 – 31 March 2007</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2007 – 31 March 2008</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2008 – 31 March 2009</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2009 – 31 March 2010</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2010 – 31 March 2011</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2011 – 31 March 2012</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2012– 31 March 2013</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2013– 31 March 2014</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2014– 31 March 2015</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April 2015– 31 March 2016</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-05-04T15:05:31.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479098/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479098/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-16","Planning Permission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, on how many called-in planning decisions he made a decision in three months or longer in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","31383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479099","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-21","<p>The proposed changes to the National Planning Policy Framework reaffirm this Government’s commitment to increasing the supply of housing in sustainable locations. Consultation on our proposed changes closed on 22 February and we are currently analysing the responses.</p><p>We have doubled the housing budget to help deliver our ambition of one million new homes and are committed to spending £8 billion to deliver over 400,000 affordable housing starts by 2021. Negotiations over the financial settlement to deliver affordable housing within London are continuing.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-21T17:15:02.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479099/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479099/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-16","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of proposed changes to the National Planning Framework for London on the (a) availability and (b) affordability of housing in London.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","31303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479100","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-21","<p>There are some specific circumstances where there are clear opportunities for having higher density housing development while creating high quality, safe and attractive places to live.</p><p>Last December we consulted on changes to national planning policy to encourage higher densities around commuter hubs, and will publish our response to this consultation in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-21T17:13:39.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479100/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479100/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-16","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of encouraging increased residential density around business and transport hubs to reduce community demand on public and private transport.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","31331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479101","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-03-29","<p>Increasing the number of homes is a top priority for this Government and helping smaller builders to contribute is key. Self builders are exempt from the Community Infrastructure Levy and charging authorities may offer relief from the levy in exceptional circumstances where a specific scheme cannot afford to pay it.</p><p>We brought forward policy to exempt sites of less than 10 units from making affordable housing and tariff style contributions through section 106 planning obligations, which was subsequently quashed by the courts. We have appealed this decision and we are awaiting the judgment from the Court of Appeal.</p><p>The Government is currently undertaking a review of the Community Infrastructure Levy, through an independent panel, to assess the extent to which the levy provides an effective mechanism for funding infrastructure, and to recommend changes that would improve its operation in support of the Government’s wider housing and growth objectives. The review, amongst other issues, will be looking at the relationship between the levy and section 106, including how they work together in practice.</p><p /><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-03-29T14:13:11.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479101/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479101/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-03-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department has taken to encourage the development of small sites by small builders; and whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential effect of deferring payment of the community infrastructure levy for sites of less than 50 units until those properties are placed on the market on the development of such sites.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","31362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479102","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-22","<p>I am considering Ofcom’s report on the independent production sector regulations and will respond in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-22T09:53:28.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479102/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479102/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Broadcasting Programmes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when he plans to respond to Ofcom's review of the Terms of Trade.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","31314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479104","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Resource DEL budget (excluding depreciation) for 2015-16 in the Autumn Statement 2015 reflected the Main Estimate cover of £1,140m; the Resource DEL budget (excluding depreciation) for 2015-16 in the Budget 2016 reflected the Supplementary Estimate cover of £1,166m. The movements that make up the change of £25,899,000 are scheduled on pages 507-508 of the Supplementary Estimate 2015-16.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-21T13:27:06.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479104/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479104/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Departmental Expenditure Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 78 in the Autumn Statement 2015 and page 91 of the Budget 2016, for what reason the estimate of his Resource DEL budget for 2015-16 has changed from £1.1 billion to £1.2 billion.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479105","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Capital DEL budget for 2015-16 in the Autumn Statement 2015 reflected the Main Estimate cover of £402m; the Capital DEL budget for 2015-16 in the Budget 2016 reflected the Supplementary Estimate cover of £368m. The movements that make up the change of £33,928,000 are scheduled on page 509 of the Supplementary Estimate 2015-16.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-21T13:28:29.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479105/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479105/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Departmental Expenditure Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 79 in the Autumn Statement 2015 and page 92 in the Budget 2016, for what reason the estimate of his Capital DEL budget for 2015-16 has changed from £0.4 billion to £0.3 billion.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479106","Department for Education","false","2016-03-24","<p>As announced in Budget 2016, a new soft drinks industry levy is expected to raise £520 million in the first year.</p><p> </p><p>In England, revenue from the soft drinks industry levy will be used to double the Physical Education (PE) and sport premium for primary schools from £160 million a year to £320 million from September 2017. Primary schools will be able to make further improvements to the quality and breadth of PE and sport they offer, including introducing new activities, after school clubs and hiring specialist coaches to work alongside teachers.</p><p> </p><p>Revenue generated from the levy will also be used to provide up to £285 million a year to give 25% of secondary schools increased opportunity to extend their school day to offer a wider range of activities for pupils. This can include sports clubs.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","31426","2016-03-24T17:03:32.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479106/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479106/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-03-16","Sugar: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 33 of the Budget 2016, how much of the £520 million estimated to be raised by the new sugar levy she expects to be allocated to sporting initiatives through her Department's budget or arms length bodies in each of the next four years.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479107","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-21","<p>At Budget 2016 the Government announced an intention to establish a Broadband Investment Fund. No decision has yet been made on the amount that will be invested. The next stage of the process will see the Government procure a fund manager to raise and manage the fund.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-21T13:23:07.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479107/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479107/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 65 of the Budget, how much he expects to contribute from his Departmental resources to establish the new Broadband Investment Fund in (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479108","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-22","<p>The Government announced a range of investments in arts projects across the country in the 2016 Budget. This included £1 million for the refurbishment of Drapers Hall in the 2017/18 financial year.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-22T09:55:12.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479108/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479108/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Historic Buildings: Coventry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of his Department's spend on the refurbishment of Drapers' Hall, Coventry in each of the next five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","31382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479109","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>Departmental budgets were set out at Spending Review 2015. Budget 2016 set out that around £1.5 billion capital investment in areas such as housing, schools and transport will be accelerated.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-24T17:07:10.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479109/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479109/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Departmental Expenditure Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 92 of the Budget 2016, what steps he is taking to respond to planned changes to his Capital DEL in 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479110","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Budget sets out that the government will find a further £3.5 billion of savings from public spending in 2019-20, building on the plans set out at Spending Review 2015. To inform future spending decisions and the delivery of these savings, the government is launching an efficiency review. The Chief Secretary to the Treasury, with the support of the Paymaster General, will lead this efficiency review, which will report in 2018. The Department for Culture Media and Sport will actively support this review.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-24T17:06:01.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479110/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479110/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Departmental Expenditure Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to page 91 of the Budget 2016, what steps he is taking to respond to planned changes to his Resource DEL in 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479111","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-23","Public libraries are funded and run by local authorities. My Department has through Arts Council England’s Library Development Funding, which supports the development of public libraries in England including workforce training, provided £680,000 in 2012/13; £683,000 in 2013/14; £595,000 in 2014/15; and £744,000 in 2015/16. Workforce development is also one of the priorities of the Leadership for Libraries Taskforce, established in 2015 by my Department and the Local Government Association.","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","31479 ; 31482","2016-03-23T10:55:29.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479111/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479111/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Public Libraries: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his Department's planned expenditure on workforce training for staff in public libraries is for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479112","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-23","Public libraries are funded and run by local authorities. However, through the Government's development agency for public libraries, Arts Council England, funding is provided to support public libraries in England, some of which will fund computer facilities. Specific detail of this funding is not available. Future Arts Council England investment plans for public libraries will be developed following proposals from partner organisations.<p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","31480 ; 31481","2016-03-23T10:58:23.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479112/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479112/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Public Libraries: Computers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his Department's planned expenditure on computer facilities for public libraries is for (a) 2016-17, (b) 2017-18, (c) 2018-19 and (d) 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479113","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Government is currently working with the BBC to come to an agreed estimate of the likely revenue impact. These measures are being introduced to ensure that payment of the licence fee is fair for the public and that those who enjoy BBC content pay the licence fee accordingly.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-21T13:23:56.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479113/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479113/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the potential additional revenue that would be generated for the BBC by extending the licence fee to include viewing content on iPlayer.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479114","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Department has made no estimation of the number of jobs that would be created by the Digital Single Market. According to the European Parliament, completing the Digital Single Market could add €415bn or around 3% to the EU’s GDP.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-24T14:53:08.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479114/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479114/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-16","Digital Technology: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many jobs his Department estimates would be created by the completion of the Digital Single Market.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479115","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-29","<p>The Creative Europe Desk UK, which is part-funded by DCMS, raises awareness of the opportunities offered by the EU’s Creative Europe programme; encourages the UK’s creative sectors to engage in the programme through taking part in supported international initiatives and networks‎; and provides advice and support to UK-based applicants of Creative Europe. The Desk is led by the British Council and the BFI with a consortium of partners in the UK (Arts Council England, Creative Scotland, Arts Council of Northern Ireland, Welsh Government).</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-29T09:28:16.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479115/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479115/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Arts: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to help arts and cultural organisations apply for funding from the EU's Creative Europe programme.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479116","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-22","<p>In November 2015, the Prime Minister announced the Government’s intention to introduce a broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) with the ambition to give people the legal right to request a connection to broadband with speeds of 10 Megabits per second (Mbps), no matter where they live. We intend to publish a consultation on our approach to introducing a broadband USO shortly, and will respond to that consultation in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-22T11:42:51.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479116/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479116/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when his Department plans to publish the results of the consultation into a universal service obligation for superfast broadband.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479117","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-21","<p>In April 2015 the previous Government introduced regulations requiring authorisation of stakes over £50 on Fixed Odds Betting Terminals through a “verified account” or staff interaction.The Government published its evaluation of the £50 regulations on 21 January, which can be found here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-gaming-machine-circumstances-of-useamendment-regulations-2015</p><p> </p><p>We will now consider the findings of the evaluation before deciding if there is a need for further action.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-21T15:39:27.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479117/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479117/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when his Department plans to publish its Triennial Review of gambling machine stakes and prize limits; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479118","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-22","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-22T09:49:28.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479118/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479118/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the potential effects of the UK leaving the EU on arts and culture in the UK.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479119","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-22","<p>Public libraries are funded and run by local authorities. However, the Government provided funding in 2015-16 which means that by March 2016, free WiFi will be available in 99% of public libraries in England. In total, 70 local authorities will have received funding of around £2.7 million to upgrade or install WiFi in 1017 public libraries. In addition, through the Government’s super connected cities programme, WiFi was previously installed in 288 libraries across 14 cities, UK-wide by the end of March 2015.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","31478 ; 31483","2016-03-22T11:40:57.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479119/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479119/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Public Libraries: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his Department's expenditure was on Wi-Fi provision for public libraries in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14, (e) 2014-15 and (f) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479120","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-23","<p>DCMS is engaging with national Digital Engagement partners to help users of public libraries get online and to tackle digital exclusion. Thanks to Government funding, over 99% of public libraries in England will provide free access to Wi-Fi from March 2016. BT and Barclays have worked together to provide free Wi-Fi in 100 libraries and community centres in deprived areas across England; and Lloyds Banking Group and Halifax Community Bank have piloted a scheme to match local branch staff with libraries to deliver basic digital skills training to adults in the UK. Tackling digital exclusion is also one of the priorities of the Leadership for Libraries Taskforce, established in 2015 by DCMS and the Local Government Association. The Taskforce has been working in partnership with the Tinder Foundation on new approaches through libraries to build digital skills in socially excluded, hard to reach groups and address digital exclusion.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-23T10:51:22.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479120/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479120/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Public Libraries: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to provide assistance to public libraries to address digital exclusion.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479121","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-23","<p>We published our Culture White Paper today. I refer the hon Member to my Statement HCWS643.</p><p>The white paper is attached and is in the library of the House.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-23T13:33:34.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479121/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479121/answer","DCMS_The_Culture_White_Paper__1_.pdf","DCMS The Culture White Paper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479121/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when his Department plans to publish its White Paper on the arts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479122","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-23","<p>In the last year, £39 million has been invested across the country on artificial grass pitches in Buckinghamshire, Berkshire, Hampshire, London, Manchester, Devon, Essex, Staffordshire, West Riding, Middlesex, Wiltshire, Durham, Liverpool, Lincolnshire, Staffordshire, North Riding, Lancashire, Hertfordshire, Birmingham Northumberland, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Nottinghamshire, Surrey, Dorset, Cumberland and East Riding. Further details on the individual grants awarded are available from the Football Foundation.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is also investing £8 million over the next 4 years in Parklife, to increase the number of full-size publicly accessible artificial grass pitches in England by 50 per cent. The Football Association is matching government funding, with further contributions from the Premier League and Local Authorities in this new £200 million grassroots facilities investment programme.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-23T15:24:05.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479122/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479122/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Football: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many artificial football pitches in which locations have been supported by funding from his Department since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479123","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-22","<p>There are currently plans to host a roundtable with representatives from all sides of the argument to discuss ad blocking in the coming weeks. Once we have heard their views, we will consider what role there is for Government.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-22T11:44:11.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479123/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479123/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Internet: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, on what date his Department plans to host a round table on ad blocking; who he plans to invite to that event; and what outcomes he expects from that event.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479124","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-24","<p>Since 2010/11, the Government has invested over £125 million with the specific purpose of creating and maintaining new artificial grass pitches (AGPs) delivered by the Football Foundation, Sport England (whose investment includes AGPs for football, and multi-sport projects/facilities) and Parklife football hubs programme. This investment came to £8,925,413 in 2010/11; £11,958,279 in 2011/12; £18,107,308 in 2012/13; £26,996,902 in 2013/14; £31,751,581 in 2014/15; and £27,407,989 in 2015/16 to date.</p><p> </p><p>Government funding in the Football Foundation has been matched by the Premier League and the Football Association.</p>","Bexleyheath and Crayford","David Evennett",,"2016-03-24T11:52:48.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479124/answer","Biography information for Sir David Evennett","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479124/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Football: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his Department's expenditure was on artificial football pitches in  (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12, (c) 2012-13, (d) 2013-14, (e) 2014-15 and (f) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479125","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-22","<p>Listed places of worship represent some of the nation’s finest heritage. Since 2015 DCMS has provided £30m of financial support to 502 places of worship across the UK for essential roof repairs. Applications opened for a further funding round of £25m in December 2015. Successful applicants will be announced in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-22T09:51:54.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479125/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479125/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Religious Buildings: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many places of worship have received financial support from his Department for essential roof repairs since 2015.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479126","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-03-29","<p>The Creative Europe Programme (2014-2020) was launched in January 2014. The programme consists of two sub-programmes; the Culture sub-programme to promote the culture sector, and the MEDIA sub-programme to support the audiovisual sector. Prior to 2014, the European Commission ran separate Culture and MEDIA programmes.</p><p> </p><p>The Creative Europe UK Desk reports the following support was received by UK cultural and creative organisations and audiovisual companies through each of the sub-programmes in 2013, 2014 and 2015.</p><p> </p><p>UK Results for EU Commission Culture and MEDIA programmes 2013, and Creative Europe Programme 2014-2015</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>MEDIA</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Culture</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Direct Grants</p></td><td><p>Indirect Funding</p></td><td><p>Direct Grants</p></td><td><p>Indirect Funding</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>€ 7,688,041</p></td><td><p>€ 6,118,515</p></td><td><p>€ 4,825,000</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>€ 9,289,292</p></td><td><p>€ 7,775,310</p></td><td><p>€ 5,880,208</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>€ 6,677,272</p></td><td><p>€ 4,745,231</p></td><td><p>€ 5,451,385</p></td><td><p>N/A</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Note: Indirect funding in the MEDIA sub-programme relates to awards to non-UK distribution companies distributing UK films in foreign markets. In the Culture sub-programme all awards are direct grants to UK led projects.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-03-29T09:26:40.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479126/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/479126/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-03-16","Arts: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what (a) grants and (b) indirect funding were provided by the EU's Creative Europe programme the UK arts and cultural organisations in (i) 2013-14, (ii) 2014-15 and (iii) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","31508"
